Direct from the horse's mouth:

...

Yes yes! The time has come to move to a venue a little more our speed: Darker, dirtier, grittier, louder, closer into the center of everything. Nickie's on Lower Haight is just the spot, and I've been eyeing it up and down for a while. So we snatched up Wednesdays really quickly, and we're running with it as hard as we can. And we just couldn't resist the name "Crooked," knowing the way things usually get at Nickie's. 

m.d.K, Erok, Marc(O) and I (the newly formed "Renegade Ferrets version 1.2") will be holding it down, bringing in very special guests from around the Bay and beyond every week. We go from 10pm 'til 2am at Nickie's, and, unfortunately, we can't keep the free door hook-ups that we used to have at @lpha - we've got to charge $3 at the door at Crooked. But come on, $3... that's less than the cost of a drink! And well worth it for the lineups we plan to put together on a weekly basis. 

For our premiere show, next week, August 9th, we're gonna kick it off with a lineup that's a bit of a preview of the type of night we want this to be every time (with an admitted bit of overkill on the numbers, since this one's special) - a few of our favorites all coming together for one wicked night of breaks: 

Kapt'n Kirk 
Ernie Trevino 
Ripple 
Satsi 
Evinrude 

So come out, have a drink with us, say hello, and help us usher in Crooked, a brand-new way to do Wednesday nights. 

Oh yeah, I almost forgot: 

GET BENT!!! 


Wednesday, August 9th 
CROOKED Premiere 
Nickie's BBQ 
460 Haight St. @ Fillmore, SF 
10pm-2am, $3, 21+ with ID 
--NextPart_Webmail_9m3u9jl4l_21223_1154456412_0--

sorry to hear about your loss; i hope you find your records...
for future reference, it is commonly advised to call all major and local record stores that buy used music (rasputin, amoeba, etc...)
let them know the situation, along with some of the titles in your bag... if the thief is not wise and tries selling them, employees will be advised to make low-ball offers... you can then by back your music at a much-discounted price...
good luck...


Ranger - <plurranger@hotmail.com> wrote: Shelly.. so sorry to hear that as well.  I will definitely keep an eye and

people have them.. if they turn up on the decks I only hope peoples keep and 
ear out.  Best wishes and let's get you some new chunes.

Ranger

From: Calamity Jane 
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Subject: [sfraves] stolen records
Date: Mon, 31 Jul 2006 11:43:14 -0700 (PDT)

hey guys,

friday night, word of mouth held a party in the
bayview area.  i'm tossing this request out to anyone
who might have attended, who might have seen something
- anything.  i was hoping after a couple days that i'd
hear word from someone that my bag was in a crew
member's car from strike and they just didn't see it,
but that hasn't happened.

my record bag is a black technics soft case with a
pair of silver sony's in the front pocket, and about
40 tech-house and breaks records with a few downtempo
in the front.  this soft case doesn't have any padding
- it looks more like a shoulder bag, and
on the front is technics written in white script.
it's also a little ripped up and abused but there are
no distinguishable stickers or writing on it.  this is
a small list of records that i can remember having in
there:

Alex Under - "Sorbere Cerebros EP"  [Trapez]
Ben-G - "Barnadango"  [Funkdango]
Jamie Anderson - "Counter Strike"  [Fixia]
Jake Childs & LBO - "Invisible Inc EP"  [Uniform
Black]
Chus Duran - "So Fresh"  [Funkdango]
Claude Young - "Electronic Dissident"  [Dust Science]
Bobby Peru - "Blood Money"  [2020 Vision]
Prefuse 73 - "92 Vs. 02 Collection" [Warp Records]
Tosca - "Dehli9" [K7]

it was in my back seat (i have a dark blue jetta with
a 'i hate your suv' sticker on the back). we arrived
at the loc. around 9:30pm to offload, and i'll be
honest - i didn't unload it from my car. i grabbed
larger items from the back, dropped them off, and when
i came back it wasn't there anymore - it was assumedly
brought to the location by a crew member and i left it
at that.  strike came around and it still wasn't
anywhere.

any information - anything at all - that you may have
about my bag would be greatly appreciated.  if you saw
it, where you saw it and WHEN you saw it would be
incredibly helpful.

you can reach me anytime via this email addy -

thanks,
shelley

Uhh,

apot <djapot@yahoo.com> wrote:
  you know, it's very naive to point out a single material event to claim
that someone sucks and is the worst such-and-such...

Excuse me this is not a single event this is thousands of events.

<djapot@yahoo.com> wrote
(but you really have to look at the full spectrum of their actions and
initiatives... i grew up in times square, in the 80's... if you knew
anything about nyc or spent significant time there, then you'll know that
giuliani is responsible for turning that area from a decadent porn, hooker,
and drug den into a booming economic and tourist haven...)

This is not a tourist heaven , this is a corporate franchise today, there is
nothing interesting about , McDonalds, Disney, on and on, cheap broadway
thrillers. And the hoods are just around the corner. I was there in the 80's
, I liked  it . Its was so colorfull , and interesting ,free, a unique
place. 
By the way, whats wrong with "decadent porn" are you a christion moralist. I
think amsterdam has much more "decadent porn" than times square did. You
must be a voting member of the republican party, so naturally you would not
like these things. 
  But lets be fair, and give credit where it is do, Adolph would have been a
great cop. His guilty feelings about his father being in the Mafia and going
to Sing Sing for most of his childhood (his dad jacked the mail man, federal
offense). Rudolph should have never been mayor, but would have been a good
policeman with a liberal mayor, one more tastefull and resptfull for the
arts to keep him in line.
  I like the way the mayor of Berlin allways address's the attendee's of the
Popkomm festival with a welcome letter, to  all the participants and diverse
Independent techno labels. In Guiliani's eyes we were all "evil doers"
Love Parade in NY, I don't think so.

We're not talking about "explicit illegal activity" for events. We're
talking about places like the Cooler, Baktun, Filter 14 (jacky 60's)
,cbgb's, knitting factory and more clean fully legal venues being closed or
coming close to closure because of Adlophs policies.  In short you seen to
not really understand the depth of these problems. Which I why I write about
it because it amazes me how many people don't realize what happened there
and could happen elsewhere.

Ive personally have thrown close to 400 events in NY city, LEGAL events and
I know what I'm talking about. There are no exagerations in what I'm
writing.
 
<djapot@yahoo.com> wrote
(if you're looking to throw  events with explicit illegal activity, think of
ug's as an alternative... last i heard, queens and brooklyn were still great
places to throw parties...
just saying..).

X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: RE: [sfraves] Renegade Violence Friday Night

I just wanted to cross-post the comments from the incident that happened at 
the WOM crews party Friday night which are effects from inner city late 
night parties in remote locations that should get everyone thinkign about 
the safety of the party-goers.. an important issue for sure.


This from tribe:

Gang violence at Friday's renegadeToday, 10:26 AM

On Friday night there was a renegade on the jetty near pound SF. Great 
party, good vibe, lots of friendly diverse people, top notch music and some 
excellent fire spinning. Around 4:30 several unfriendly local thugs stumbled 
upon the party with eyes wide like they had just found a liquor store with 
no attendant. They approached 2 party partygoers and robbed them at 
gunpoint. They took everything these kids had on them and before the 
incident was finished, one of them had been pistol-whipped across the face. 
While I did not witness the actual event, I did watch the aftermath unfold. 
The injured kid was pretty beaten up, and bleeding… his friends took him to 
the hospital and the party was shut down almost immediately. We got out of 
there as quickly as possible, shocked and disturbed by what had happened.

Nobody could have anticipated something like this and nobody is to blame for 
what happened. In reflecting on this situation it occurred to me that we 
spend a lot of time in dodgy neighborhoods (both inside and out,) off our 
heads, partying without a care in the world… and yes, that is what a 
renegade is all about. But, paying attention to what is going on around you 
and being able to react to safety concerns is of the utmost importance. This 
could have happened anywhere, to anyone and it’s very unfortunate that it 
happened on Friday. A major lesson learned is simple awareness of your 
surroundings at all times, especially when you are outside, at night, in one 
of the worst neighborhoods in the city. I think the crew throwing this party 
reacted in an excellent way by ensuring that the injured party kid got a 
ride to the hospital and shutting down the party as soon as possible. In my 
discussions of this on Saturday and Sunday I discovered that False Profit 
hired a security guard for their most recent renegade due to the 
neighborhood that they had chosen (hunters point area). It’s possible that a 
security guard may have prevented this situation – but it’s also very 
possible that they would have had no impact.

I am posting this on a few tribes with the intention of drumming up some 
conversation and awareness regarding safety concerns at parties around the 
city. I think it’s really important to discuss incidents like this and learn 
from them to improve the quality of our enjoyment and the safety at events 
like this. This was the first time I have ever even heard of violence like 
this at a party… sure, the cops have invaded our good times on occasion, but 
never a group of violent gun-toting gangsters.



SFR: Ranger
San Francisco
plurranger@hotmail.com
Who knows where the night leads
It's dark and no one can see

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: Folded @ Anu this Friday w/ Bryan Jones!

We're very lucky to have Chicago's Bryan Jones at Anu this month! Widely
known as one half of High Caliber, Bryan is one of house music's fastest
rising stars, with a plethora of recent solo releases on labels such as
Fetish, Jackin' Tracks, Black Cherry, Aroma, Robsoul, and his own imprint
Control Recordings.  Also joining us this month will be In House's Leonard
and Naz.  Get ready to jack!

.folded. @ Anu (43 Sixth St. @ Market, SF)

Friday, August 4th, 10PM - 2AM

*No Cover* as always

----

This Month Features:

Bryan Jones - Chicago (control, aroma, fetish)

Naz (in house)

Leonard (in house)

Sen-Sei (turnaround-sound)

Origami (newstylesound, so sound)

Andrew Phelan (prismatic, so sound)

Subject: [sfraves] Put the Needle on the Record

Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"



Put the Needle on the Record (<http://www.imdb.com/Sections/Years/2006>2006) 

'PUT THE NEEDLE ON THE RECORD' is an award-winning documentary which explores the evolution of electronic music and the rise of the DJ in pop culture. Filmed in Miami during the Winter Music Conference, a yearly week-long event attended by over 20,000 electronic music professionals and fans, the film takes an inside look at a growing global phenomenon in the world of music. Interviews with top artists, footage from events around the globe and a brilliant soundtrack are combined to create a highly energetic piece of filmmaking. 

See review:  http://www.newswiretoday.com/news/7325/

Subject: [sfraves] Gangs, Politics & House Music: The History of Hip Hop in
  Chicago.

--=====================_1811031==.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"


Gangs, Politics & House Music: The History of Hip Hop in Chicago. 

An interview with Jitu of the pioneering hip hop group Ten Tray By Davey D

Nowadays it’s hard to turn on the radio and not hear music from one of Chicago’s many music superstars. Common, Twista, Da Brat, Shawnna, R Kelly, Doe or Die, Crucial Conflict, Lupe Fiasco, and of course Kanye West seem to have firmly positioned themselves on the nation’s airwaves. 

If you dig a little deeper and check out Hip Hop’s underground, you’ll discover that very few people are willing to roll up and do battle with esteemed Chi-town lyricists like M’Rald, Rhymefest and of course Juice. Others like DJ Third Rail and the late DJ Pinkhouse to name a few have not only made names for themselves as deejays not to be toyed with but also provided important platform for local artists.

Yes, the Chi seems to have established itself in the world of Hip Hop, but it wasn’t always like that. In fact much of the Chi-Town’s success is a direct result of organized effort by it’s pioneering Hip Hop community that grew frustrated from being locked out by the industry that saw Chicago, more as a consumer market as a opposed to a place where stars are born. 

Many within the music industry were only willing to embrace the nation’s third largest city as the Mecca for House Music and somehow managed to disconnect that music form from Hip Hop when in many ways the two are intertwined, especially along the lines of deejay culture. 

The battle to establish ‘Tha Chi’ within Hip Hop was about as brutal as its political landscape. Unsung heroes like Dr Groove, Lord Cashus D, DA Smart, Black Allies, Sugar Ray Dinky, George Daniels, World wide Posse, God Squad, The Chi Rock Nation, Ill State Assassins, and the late DJ Pink House all played crucial roles in organizing, pushing the envelop and seeing to it that the Windy City get its respect. They used to roll up on nightclubs, radio stations and even label executives demanding to be recognized. Many will forget that back in the late 80s there was a movement called the New World Order which brought many of Chicago’s Hip Hop community together as they fought for change and respect.

CONTINUED:  http://www.thuglifearmy.com/news/?id=2903

 


MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo 

Tribenet:   <http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k>http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k 
                
House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"Americans like to talk about (or be told about) Democracy but, when put to the test, usually find it to be an 'inconvenience.' We have opted instead for an authoritarian system disguised as a Democracy. We pay through the nose for an enormous joke-of-a-government, let it push us around, and then wonder how all those assholes got in there." - Frank Zappa 

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Subject: [sfraves] What is up with the needle and the inner circle of the record.

------=_Part_21475_6823984.1154643714825
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1; format=flowed
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit

The needle has not been used much lately. Need a job. Tired of searching.
Tired of interviews. Tired of life?

The funds run red, the crops dry up, the poppies run out...

This pain in my gut. This pain in my gut. I have done it to myself with my
eyes wide open. Gosh, the stress is relentless. I owe but yet I'm owed.

Bought Biosphere - Substrata and listened closely. I found different
feelings and places. Different moods and colors. I highly recommend it to
anyone looking for a great ambient CD. Warm, yet cold, cold, yet fixed.

Finished two more tracks. My CD now has 14 songs on it. but no capital to
get mastered or pressed at this time. Is it even worth it anyway?

'Scissors for Lefty' play Friday in San Jose. Live 105 seems to be all over
them,. People should go.

Much love to all those that participate in this place and time.


-- 
Steve Osteen is SlumberMachine
http://www.SlumberMachine.com

------=_Part_21475_6823984.1154643714825--

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Photos of RedstickWOMAN and DJ Bambi

that's our interactive remix-o-musical sound installation, the 
improbable orchestra.

http://www.improbableorchestra.com/

you can't have it!  ;)  but actually, we are beginning work on a home 
version.  if you've got any requests or feedback i'd be curious to hear 
it, since we're in the early planning stages of the next generation of 
the thing right now.

io is usually at burning man but may or may not make it out there this 
year.  look for it anyway! (we usually put it way out the past the man 
somewhere) ...if it's not there you'll probably find something else 
worthwhile.

-jacob

Subject: RE: [sfraves] Renegade Violence Friday Night

That sucks big time.

Many years ago, I was at a warehouse party near Santa Cruz. They had a big
security guy working the door. A few local gangsters showed up and tried to
get but instead scuffled with the security and were sent on their way.

They came back with a rifle and started shooting through the warehouse's
closed roll up door. A few people took some bullets including one guy who
got hit in the head and died.








> -----Original Message-----
> From: Ranger - [mailto:plurranger@hotmail.com]
> Sent: Tuesday, August 01, 2006 4:31 PM
> To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
> Subject: RE: [sfraves] Renegade Violence Friday Night
> 
> I just wanted to cross-post the comments from the incident that happened
> at
> the WOM crews party Friday night which are effects from inner city late
> night parties in remote locations that should get everyone thinkign about
> the safety of the party-goers.. an important issue for sure.
> 
> 
> This from tribe:
> 
> Gang violence at Friday's renegadeToday, 10:26 AM
> 
> On Friday night there was a renegade on the jetty near pound SF. Great
> party, good vibe, lots of friendly diverse people, top notch music and
> some
> excellent fire spinning. Around 4:30 several unfriendly local thugs
> stumbled
> upon the party with eyes wide like they had just found a liquor store with
> no attendant. They approached 2 party partygoers and robbed them at
> gunpoint. They took everything these kids had on them and before the
> incident was finished, one of them had been pistol-whipped across the
> face.
> While I did not witness the actual event, I did watch the aftermath
> unfold.
> The injured kid was pretty beaten up, and bleeding. his friends took him
> to
> the hospital and the party was shut down almost immediately. We got out of
> there as quickly as possible, shocked and disturbed by what had happened.
> 
> Nobody could have anticipated something like this and nobody is to blame
> for
> what happened. In reflecting on this situation it occurred to me that we
> spend a lot of time in dodgy neighborhoods (both inside and out,) off our
> heads, partying without a care in the world. and yes, that is what a
> renegade is all about. But, paying attention to what is going on around
> you
> and being able to react to safety concerns is of the utmost importance.
> This
> could have happened anywhere, to anyone and it's very unfortunate that it
> happened on Friday. A major lesson learned is simple awareness of your
> surroundings at all times, especially when you are outside, at night, in
> one
> of the worst neighborhoods in the city. I think the crew throwing this
> party
> reacted in an excellent way by ensuring that the injured party kid got a
> ride to the hospital and shutting down the party as soon as possible. In
> my
> discussions of this on Saturday and Sunday I discovered that False Profit
> hired a security guard for their most recent renegade due to the
> neighborhood that they had chosen (hunters point area). It's possible that
> a
> security guard may have prevented this situation - but it's also very
> possible that they would have had no impact.
> 
> I am posting this on a few tribes with the intention of drumming up some
> conversation and awareness regarding safety concerns at parties around the
> city. I think it's really important to discuss incidents like this and
> learn
> from them to improve the quality of our enjoyment and the safety at events
> like this. This was the first time I have ever even heard of violence like
> this at a party. sure, the cops have invaded our good times on occasion,
> but
> never a group of violent gun-toting gangsters.
> 
> 
> 
> SFR: Ranger
> San Francisco
> plurranger@hotmail.com
> Who knows where the night leads
> It's dark and no one can see
> 
> 
> 
>

I was there too. J-Bot who then just went by his name,
James was spnning, and  I was leaning on the roll-up
door when the shots came through. One of my friends
got shot in the leg. I was the first person to get to
the guy who died, and my old friend Jason aka: snappy
did what EMT stuff he could.

That party left me tripped out for weeks. It occurred
in the late Spring of 1993.

I still have the newspaper article about what happened. The police caught
the guys who did it the same night. They were driving around Watsonville
with the gun in the car. 

There was no phone in that warehouse and a friend and I had to jump a fence
in the back and run to a neighbor's house about 1/4 mile down the road where
they called the police and ambulance.

I remember that someone was filming the party all night with a camera on a
tripod in the corner. Apparently, they used the footage at the trial as it
showed people getting shot-up.

> > >
> > > I just wanted to cross-post the comments from the
> > incident that happened
> > > at
> > > the WOM crews party Friday night which are effects
> > from inner city late
> > > night parties in remote locations that should get
> > everyone thinkign about
> > > the safety of the party-goers.. an important issue
> > for sure.
> > >
> > >
> > > This from tribe:
> > >
> > > Gang violence at Friday's renegadeToday, 10:26 AM
> > >
> > > On Friday night there was a renegade on the jetty
> > near pound SF. Great
> > > party, good vibe, lots of friendly diverse people,
> > top notch music and
> > > some
> > > excellent fire spinning. Around 4:30 several
> > unfriendly local thugs
> > > stumbled
> > > upon the party with eyes wide like they had just
> > found a liquor store with
> > > no attendant. They approached 2 party partygoers
> > and robbed them at
> > > gunpoint. They took everything these kids had on
> > them and before the
> > > incident was finished, one of them had been
> > pistol-whipped across the
> > > face.
> > > While I did not witness the actual event, I did
> > watch the aftermath
> > > unfold.
> > > The injured kid was pretty beaten up, and
> > bleeding. his friends took him
> > > to
> > > the hospital and the party was shut down almost
> > immediately. We got out of
> > > there as quickly as possible, shocked and
> > disturbed by what had happened.
> > >
> > > Nobody could have anticipated something like this
> > and nobody is to blame
> > > for
> > > what happened. In reflecting on this situation it
> > occurred to me that we
> > > spend a lot of time in dodgy neighborhoods (both
> > inside and out,) off our
> > > heads, partying without a care in the world. and
> > yes, that is what a
> > > renegade is all about. But, paying attention to
> > what is going on around
> > > you
> > > and being able to react to safety concerns is of
> > the utmost importance.
> > > This
> > > could have happened anywhere, to anyone and it's
> > very unfortunate that it
> > > happened on Friday. A major lesson learned is
> > simple awareness of your
> > > surroundings at all times, especially when you are
> > outside, at night, in
> > > one
> > > of the worst neighborhoods in the city. I think
> > the crew throwing this
> > > party
> > > reacted in an excellent way by ensuring that the
> > injured party kid got a
> > > ride to the hospital and shutting down the party
> > as soon as possible. In
> > > my
> > > discussions of this on Saturday and Sunday I
> > discovered that False Profit
> > > hired a security guard for their most recent
> > renegade due to the
> > > neighborhood that they had chosen (hunters point
> > area). It's possible that
> > > a
> > > security guard may have prevented this situation -
> > but it's also very
> > > possible that they would have had no impact.
> > >
> > > I am posting this on a few tribes with the
> > intention of drumming up some
> > > conversation and awareness regarding safety
> > concerns at parties around the
> > > city. I think it's really important to discuss
> > incidents like this and
> > > learn
> > > from them to improve the quality of our enjoyment
> > and the safety at events
> > > like this. This was the first time I have ever
> > even heard of violence like
> > > this at a party. sure, the cops have invaded our
> > good times on occasion,
> > > but
> > > never a group of violent gun-toting gangsters.
> > >
> > >
> > >

OMG you guys.. Eric.. fucking trippin dude.  Man.. the whole concept of gang 
violence and raving just blows me away.  I have never known anything but 
plur and am so happy for it.. I think it is why I am still not jaded.. and 
more seriously.. I still think that although random.. there are things we 
can do to prevent and protect the community.. like planning parties with 
safety in mind.

I just cross posted that as a wake up call to event planners.. "please keep 
patron safety in mind"  we will love you for it all the more!



SFR: Ranger
San Francisco
plurranger@hotmail.com

It's dark and no one can see





From: Eric Spire <ericspire@yahoo.com>
To: Sean <freakzone@mindspring.com>, sfraves@hyperreal.org
Subject: RE: [sfraves] Renegade Violence Friday Night
Date: Thu, 3 Aug 2006 19:22:45 -0700 (PDT)

I was there too. J-Bot who then just went by his name,
James was spnning, and  I was leaning on the roll-up
door when the shots came through. One of my friends
got shot in the leg. I was the first person to get to
the guy who died, and my old friend Jason aka: snappy
did what EMT stuff he could.

That party left me tripped out for weeks. It occurred
in the late Spring of 1993.

E


--- Sean <freakzone@mindspring.com> wrote:

 > That sucks big time.
 >
 > Many years ago, I was at a warehouse party near
 > Santa Cruz. They had a big
 > security guy working the door. A few local gangsters
 > showed up and tried to
 > get but instead scuffled with the security and were
 > sent on their way.
 >
 > They came back with a rifle and started shooting
 > through the warehouse's
 > closed roll up door. A few people took some bullets
 > including one guy who
 > got hit in the head and died.

 > > -----Original Message-----

 > > I just wanted to cross-post the comments from the
 > incident that happened
 > > at
 > > the WOM crews party Friday night which are effects
 > from inner city late
 > > night parties in remote locations that should get
 > everyone thinkign about
 > > the safety of the party-goers.. an important issue
 > for sure.
 > >
 > >
 > > This from tribe:
 > >
 > > Gang violence at Friday's renegadeToday, 10:26 AM
 > >
 > > On Friday night there was a renegade on the jetty
 > near pound SF. Great
 > > party, good vibe, lots of friendly diverse people,
 > top notch music and
 > > some
 > > excellent fire spinning. Around 4:30 several
 > unfriendly local thugs
 > > stumbled
 > > upon the party with eyes wide like they had just
 > found a liquor store with
 > > no attendant. They approached 2 party partygoers
 > and robbed them at
 > > gunpoint. They took everything these kids had on
 > them and before the
 > > incident was finished, one of them had been
 > pistol-whipped across the
 > > face.
 > > While I did not witness the actual event, I did
 > watch the aftermath
 > > unfold.
 > > The injured kid was pretty beaten up, and
 > bleeding. his friends took him
 > > to
 > > the hospital and the party was shut down almost
 > immediately. We got out of
 > > there as quickly as possible, shocked and
 > disturbed by what had happened.
 > >
 > > Nobody could have anticipated something like this
 > and nobody is to blame
 > > for
 > > what happened. In reflecting on this situation it
 > occurred to me that we
 > > spend a lot of time in dodgy neighborhoods (both
 > inside and out,) off our
 > > heads, partying without a care in the world. and
 > yes, that is what a
 > > renegade is all about. But, paying attention to
 > what is going on around
 > > you
 > > and being able to react to safety concerns is of
 > the utmost importance.
 > > This
 > > could have happened anywhere, to anyone and it's
 > very unfortunate that it
 > > happened on Friday. A major lesson learned is
 > simple awareness of your
 > > surroundings at all times, especially when you are
 > outside, at night, in
 > > one
 > > of the worst neighborhoods in the city. I think
 > the crew throwing this
 > > party
 > > reacted in an excellent way by ensuring that the
 > injured party kid got a
 > > ride to the hospital and shutting down the party
 > as soon as possible. In
 > > my
 > > discussions of this on Saturday and Sunday I
 > discovered that False Profit
 > > hired a security guard for their most recent
 > renegade due to the
 > > neighborhood that they had chosen (hunters point
 > area). It's possible that
 > > a
 > > security guard may have prevented this situation -
 > but it's also very
 > > possible that they would have had no impact.
 > >
 > > I am posting this on a few tribes with the
 > intention of drumming up some
 > > conversation and awareness regarding safety
 > concerns at parties around the
 > > city. I think it's really important to discuss
 > incidents like this and
 > > learn
 > > from them to improve the quality of our enjoyment
 > and the safety at events
 > > like this. This was the first time I have ever
 > even heard of violence like
 > > this at a party. sure, the cops have invaded our
 > good times on occasion,
 > > but
 > > never a group of violent gun-toting gangsters.
 > >
 > >

From: "Sean" <freakzone@mindspring.com>
To: <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Subject: RE: [sfraves] Renegade Violence Friday Night
Date: Thu, 3 Aug 2006 22:15:32 -0700

I still have the newspaper article about what happened. The police caught
the guys who did it the same night. They were driving around Watsonville
with the gun in the car.

There was no phone in that warehouse and a friend and I had to jump a fence
in the back and run to a neighbor's house about 1/4 mile down the road where
they called the police and ambulance.

I remember that someone was filming the party all night with a camera on a
tripod in the corner. Apparently, they used the footage at the trial as it
showed people getting shot-up.

 > > > renegade is all about. But, paying attention to
 > > what is going on around
 > > > you
 > > > and being able to react to safety concerns is of
 > > the utmost importance.
 > > > This
 > > > could have happened anywhere, to anyone and it's
 > > very unfortunate that it
 > > > happened on Friday. A major lesson learned is
 > > simple awareness of your
 > > > surroundings at all times, especially when you are
 > > outside, at night, in
 > > > one
 > > > of the worst neighborhoods in the city. I think
 > > the crew throwing this
 > > > party
 > > > reacted in an excellent way by ensuring that the
 > > injured party kid got a
 > > > ride to the hospital and shutting down the party
 > > as soon as possible. In
 > > > my
 > > > discussions of this on Saturday and Sunday I
 > > discovered that False Profit
 > > > hired a security guard for their most recent
 > > renegade due to the
 > > > neighborhood that they had chosen (hunters point
 > > area). It's possible that
 > > > a
 > > > security guard may have prevented this situation -
 > > but it's also very
 > > > possible that they would have had no impact.
 > > >
 > > > I am posting this on a few tribes with the
 > > intention of drumming up some
 > > > conversation and awareness regarding safety
 > > concerns at parties around the
 > > > city. I think it's really important to discuss
 > > incidents like this and
 > > > learn
 > > > from them to improve the quality of our enjoyment
 > > and the safety at events
 > > > like this. This was the first time I have ever
 > > even heard of violence like
 > > > this at a party. sure, the cops have invaded our
 > > good times on occasion,
 > > > but
 > > > never a group of violent gun-toting gangsters.
 > > >
 > > >
 > > >
 > > > SFR: Ranger
 > > > San Francisco
 > > > plurranger@hotmail.com

1. Creativity and innovation always builds on the past.
2. The past always tries to control the creativity that builds on it.
3. Free societies enable the future by living in the past.
4. Ours is a less and less a free society.

From: Eric Spire 
To: Sean , sfraves@hyperreal.org
Subject: RE: [sfraves] Renegade Violence Friday Night
Date: Thu, 3 Aug 2006 19:22:45 -0700 (PDT)

I was there too. J-Bot who then just went by his name,
James was spnning, and I was leaning on the roll-up
door when the shots came through. One of my friends
got shot in the leg. I was the first person to get to
the guy who died, and my old friend Jason aka: snappy
did what EMT stuff he could.

That party left me tripped out for weeks. It occurred
in the late Spring of 1993.

E

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Renegade Violence Friday Night

Scottsdale is a trip.. lot's of redneck violence in all the surrounding 
communities.. that fact that they made it to a nice house isn't too 
surprising.. there are a lots of REALLY nice houses out there - cause 
compared to Cali it is cheap as hell.  My ex GF's dad is one of the best 
plastic surgeons in the south west and their house is in a neighborhood 
where everyone designs and builds their own homes custom, on some mountain 
everyone climbs. Yet his son has all kinds of violent friends and is a 
braller, while the other son died from H.  Now.. you tell me where to draw 
the line.

Point is.. you can't escape redneck/gang violence without first protecting 
community.   If everyone does their job of raising conciousness, looking out 
for others, planning for safety.. I think we won't hear much more about 
violence.. cause it seems to be on an upswning.. so let's stomp it out!

>  > > > no attendant. They approached 2 party partygoers

>  > > > gunpoint. They took everything these kids had on
>  > > them and before the
>  > > > incident was finished, one of them had been
>  > > pistol-whipped across the
>  > > > face.

>  > > watch the aftermath
>  > > > unfold.

>  > > bleeding. his friends took him

>  > > > the hospital and the party was shut down almost
>  > > immediately. We got out of

>  > > and nobody is to blame
>  > > > for
>  > > > what happened. In reflecting on this situation it

2. The past always tries to control the creativity that builds on it.
3. Free societies enable the future by living in the past.
4. Ours is a less and less a free society.

> >  > > > Gang violence at Friday's renegadeToday, 10:26 AM
> >  > > >
> >  > > > On Friday night there was a renegade on the jetty
> >  > > near pound SF. Great
> >  > > > party, good vibe, lots of friendly diverse people,
> >  > > top notch music and
> >  > > > some
> >  > > > excellent fire spinning. Around 4:30 several
> >  > > unfriendly local thugs
> >  > > > stumbled
> >  > > > upon the party with eyes wide like they had just
> >  > > found a liquor store with
> >  > > > no attendant. They approached 2 party partygoers
> >  > > and robbed them at
> >  > > > gunpoint. They took everything these kids had on
> >  > > them and before the
> >  > > > incident was finished, one of them had been
> >  > > pistol-whipped across the
> >  > > > face.
> >  > > > While I did not witness the actual event, I did
> >  > > watch the aftermath
> >  > > > unfold.
> >  > > > The injured kid was pretty beaten up, and
> >  > > bleeding. his friends took him
> >  > > > to
> >  > > > the hospital and the party was shut down almost
> >  > > immediately. We got out of
> >  > > > there as quickly as possible, shocked and
> >  > > disturbed by what had happened.
> >  > > >
> >  > > > Nobody could have anticipated something like this
> >  > > and nobody is to blame
> >  > > > for
> >  > > > what happened. In reflecting on this situation it
> >  > > occurred to me that we
> >  > > > spend a lot of time in dodgy neighborhoods (both
> >  > > inside and out,) off our
> >  > > > heads, partying without a care in the world. and
> >  > > yes, that is what a
> >  > > > renegade is all about. But, paying attention to
> >  > > what is going on around
> >  > > > you
> >  > > > and being able to react to safety concerns is of
> >  > > the utmost importance.
> >  > > > This
> >  > > > could have happened anywhere, to anyone and it's
> >  > > very unfortunate that it
> >  > > > happened on Friday. A major lesson learned is
> >  > > simple awareness of your
> >  > > > surroundings at all times, especially when you are
> >  > > outside, at night, in
> >  > > > one
> >  > > > of the worst neighborhoods in the city. I think
> >  > > the crew throwing this
> >  > > > party
> >  > > > reacted in an excellent way by ensuring that the
> >  > > injured party kid got a
> >  > > > ride to the hospital and shutting down the party
> >  > > as soon as possible. In
> >  > > > my
> >  > > > discussions of this on Saturday and Sunday I
> >  > > discovered that False Profit
> >  > > > hired a security guard for their most recent
> >  > > renegade due to the
> >  > > > neighborhood that they had chosen (hunters point
> >  > > area). It's possible that
> >  > > > a
> >  > > > security guard may have prevented this situation -
> >  > > but it's also very
> >  > > > possible that they would have had no impact.
> >  > > >
> >  > > > I am posting this on a few tribes with the
> >  > > intention of drumming up some
> >  > > > conversation and awareness regarding safety
> >  > > concerns at parties around the
> >  > > > city. I think it's really important to discuss
> >  > > incidents like this and
> >  > > > learn
> >  > > > from them to improve the quality of our enjoyment
> >  > > and the safety at events
> >  > > > like this. This was the first time I have ever
> >  > > even heard of violence like
> >  > > > this at a party. sure, the cops have invaded our
> >  > > good times on occasion,
> >  > > > but
> >  > > > never a group of violent gun-toting gangsters.

-- 
1. Creativity and innovation always builds on the past.
2. The past always tries to control the creativity that builds on it.
3. Free societies enable the future by living in the past.
4. Ours is a less and less a free society.

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Renegade Violence Friday Night

Last year right around December there was an incident @ Modified where some 
gang bangers came in and started stopping people in the party and pocket 
checking them on the spot.  Eventually they were asked to leave and offered 
refunds.  I believe a fight started and all hell broke loose.  They were all 
shoved outside the venue and the door was locked but unfortunatly one of the 
guys who helps out and djs (Andrew K) was trapped outside with them.  They 
beat him up with a 2x4 and he was hospitalized for at the very minimum 
several days. He's ok now and was back on his feet pretty quickly but it 
really brings to light the dangers of us (party goers) being forced by the 
cities to throw renegade events in ghetto's.

Another event happened at the Crack House in Oakland where some gang bangers 
stole the cash box at the door and I believe fired some shots off.  These 
guys were locals and always seen hangin around the venue.  I actually 
believe there were several incidents there that compelled people to stop 
using the venue and in general brought great concern to partying in Oakland. 
PERIOD.

It just seemed like the gangtsa / ghetto people had finally figured out that 
they could swoop up on unsuspecting ravers or even force there way into 
events and do what they want.  Even when there was security present.

Its a very scary reality we have to deal with sometimes.




Paul

Subject: [sfraves] Violence and Liability....

Here's what I said in 1999 about Oakland shutting down
legal parties....

" Silver Pearl Records' Eric Spire voices the
conundrum: "It seems to me that they're trying to take
the liability away, but they may be increasing it.
They are not going to be issuing permits, but events
are going to happen within their city limits anyhow,
and they're not going to know about them." 

Going on to say that permitted events were safer,
because at least the event attendees had the
protection of the police outside the event. With no
permits, "thug" violence, muggings, vandalism, etc ...
are an obvious outcome.

.... I am also writing a little story about the party
in 1993 where the shooting happpened. I will post it
later.

At least 6 arrested at a zombie themed dance party at nicollet light rail station sat. Bail set at 30,000.00 each. charged with simulation of weapons of mass destruction for dancing to homemade radios. 

http://twincities.indymedia.org/newswire/display/28018/index.php

Subject: [sfraves] BSP:  Ryoji Ikeda - datamatics [ver.1.0b] 

--=====================_31099062==.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="iso-8859-1"
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Ryoji Ikeda - datamatics [ver.1.0b] 
Produced by forma 
www.forma.org.uk 
Commissioned by AV Festival and ZeroOne San Jose and ISEA 2006. Supported by Arts Council England, Yamaguchi Center for Arts and Media (YCAM) and Recombinant Media Labs. 

THURSDAY AUGUST 10TH 
2 sessions at 7:00pm sharp and 10:30pm 

RECOMBINANT MEDIA LABS 
San Francisco 
$15 
Reservations are strongly suggested. 
call 650.255.8947 for more info 



Using pure data as a source for sound and visuals, datamatics combines abstract and mimetic presentations of matter, time and space in a powerful and breathtakingly accomplished work. 

datamatics is the second audiovisual concert in Ryoji Ikeda?s datamatics series? an art project that explores the potential to perceive the invisible multi?substance of data that permeates our world. For datamatics [ver.1.0b], Ikeda presents a special surround-sound version of his datamatics concert. 

Projecting dynamic, computer?generated imagery ? in pared down black and white with striking colour accents, Ikeda?s intense yet minimal graphic renderings of data progress through multiple dimensions. From 2D sequences of patterns derived from hard drive errors and studies of software code, the imagery transforms into dramatic, rotating views of the universe in 3D, whilst the final scenes add a further dimension as four-dimensional mathematical processing opens up spectacular and seemingly infinite vistas. 

A powerful and hypnotic soundtrack reflects the imagery through a meticulous layering of sonic components to produce immense and apparently boundless acoustic spaces. 

datamatics? alongside the recently released and critically acclaimed dataplex album(raster-noton)? marks a significant and exciting progression in Ikeda?s work. 

Ryoji Ikeda 
Japan's leading electronic composer/artist, Ryoji Ikeda, focuses on the minutiae of ultrasonics, frequencies and the essential characteristics of sound itself. Since 1995, Ikeda has been intensely active through concerts, installations, and recordings, integrating sound, acoustics and sublime imagery. In the artist?s works, music, time and space are shaped by mathematical methods as Ikeda explores sound as sensation, pulling apart its physical properties to reveal its relationship with human perception. 

Ikeda has gained a reputation as one of the few international artists working convincingly across both visual and sonic media. Using computer and digital technologies to the utmost limit, his audiovisual concerts datamatics (2006 ? present), C4I (2004 ? present) and formula (2000 ? 2006) suggest a unique orientation for our future multimedia environment and culture. His acclaimed installations data.spectra (2005), spectra [for terminal 5, jfk] (2004), spectra II (2002) and db (2002) continue to diffuse Ikeda?s aesthetic of ?ultra minimalism? to the art world. Ikeda?s latest body of work, datamatics, is a long-term programme of moving image, sculptural, sound and new media works that use data as their theme and material to explore the ways in which abstracted views of reality ? data ? are used to encode, understand and control the world. 

He has been hailed by critics as one of the most radical and innovative contemporary composers for his live performances, sound installations and album releases. His albums +/- (Touch, 1996), 0°C (Touch, 1998) and matrix (Touch, 2000) pioneered a new minimal world of electronic music, employing sine waves, electronic "glitch" sounds, and white noise. Ikeda released his critically acclaimed, seventh solo album entitled dataplex (raster-noton), as part of the datamatics series, in 2005. 


The versatile range of Ikeda's research is demonstrated by his collaborations with Carsten Nicolai on the project cyclo. and with choreographer William Forsythe/Frankfurt Ballett, artist Hiroshi Sugimoto, architect Toyo Ito and artist collective Dumb Type, among others. 

Ikeda has exhibited and performed at many of the world's leading festivals and venues, including the Australian Centre for the Moving Image, 2005 (Melbourne); Centre Pompidou 2004 and 2001, Musée d'Art Moderne de la Ville 1999, and La Villette 2002 (all Paris); Sónar 1999 and 2006 (Barcelona); Architectural Association 2002, Barbican 2006, Hayward Gallery 2000, Millennium Dome 2000, Queen Elizabeth Hall 2000, Tate Modern Turbine Hall 2006 (all London); Auditorium Parco della Musica 2003 (Rome); ICC 1999 and 2005, Tokyo International Forum 2006 (Tokyo); Göteborg Biennial 2003 (Göteborg). In 2001, Ikeda was awarded the Ars Electronica Golden Nica prize in the digital music category and he was short-listed for a World Technology Award in 2003. 

www.ryojiikeda.com

> Ryoji Ikeda - datamatics [ver.1.0b]
> Produced by forma
> www.forma.org.uk
> Commissioned by AV Festival and ZeroOne San Jose and ISEA 2006. Supported
> by Arts Council England, Yamaguchi Center for Arts and Media (YCAM) and

>
> Using pure data as a source for sound and visuals, datamatics combines
> abstract and mimetic presentations of matter, time and space in a powerfu=
l
> and breathtakingly accomplished work.
>
> datamatics is the second audiovisual concert in Ryoji Ikeda?s datamatics
> series? an art project that explores the potential to perceive the invisi=
ble
> multi?substance of data that permeates our world. For datamatics [ver.1.0=
b],
> Ikeda presents a special surround-sound version of his datamatics concert=
.
>
> Projecting dynamic, computer?generated imagery ? in pared down black and
> white with striking colour accents, Ikeda?s intense yet minimal graphic
> renderings of data progress through multiple dimensions. From 2D sequence=
s
> of patterns derived from hard drive errors and studies of software code, =
the
> imagery transforms into dramatic, rotating views of the universe in 3D,
> whilst the final scenes add a further dimension as four-dimensional
> mathematical processing opens up spectacular and seemingly infinite vista=
s.
>
> A powerful and hypnotic soundtrack reflects the imagery through a
> meticulous layering of sonic components to produce immense and apparently
> boundless acoustic spaces.
>
> datamatics? alongside the recently released and critically acclaimed
> dataplex album(raster-noton)? marks a significant and exciting progressio=
n
> in Ikeda?s work.
>
> Ryoji Ikeda
> Japan's leading electronic composer/artist, Ryoji Ikeda, focuses on the
> minutiae of ultrasonics, frequencies and the essential characteristics of
> sound itself. Since 1995, Ikeda has been intensely active through concert=
s,
> installations, and recordings, integrating sound, acoustics and sublime
> imagery. In the artist?s works, music, time and space are shaped by
> mathematical methods as Ikeda explores sound as sensation, pulling apart =
its
> physical properties to reveal its relationship with human perception.
>
> Ikeda has gained a reputation as one of the few international artists
> working convincingly across both visual and sonic media. Using computer a=
nd
> digital technologies to the utmost limit, his audiovisual concerts
> datamatics (2006 ? present), C4I (2004 ? present) and formula (2000 ? 200=
6)
> suggest a unique orientation for our future multimedia environment and
> culture. His acclaimed installations data.spectra (2005), spectra [for
> terminal 5, jfk] (2004), spectra II (2002) and db (2002) continue to diff=
use
> Ikeda?s aesthetic of ?ultra minimalism? to the art world. Ikeda?s latest
> body of work, datamatics, is a long-term programme of moving image,
> sculptural, sound and new media works that use data as their theme and
> material to explore the ways in which abstracted views of reality ? data =
?
> are used to encode, understand and control the world.
>
> He has been hailed by critics as one of the most radical and innovative
> contemporary composers for his live performances, sound installations and
> album releases. His albums +/- (Touch, 1996), 0=B0C (Touch, 1998) and mat=
rix
> (Touch, 2000) pioneered a new minimal world of electronic music, employin=
g
> sine waves, electronic "glitch" sounds, and white noise. Ikeda released h=
is
> critically acclaimed, seventh solo album entitled dataplex (raster-noton)=
,
> as part of the datamatics series, in 2005.
>
>
> The versatile range of Ikeda's research is demonstrated by his
> collaborations with Carsten Nicolai on the project cyclo. and with
> choreographer William Forsythe/Frankfurt Ballett, artist Hiroshi Sugimoto=
,
> architect Toyo Ito and artist collective Dumb Type, among others.
>
> Ikeda has exhibited and performed at many of the world's leading festival=
s
> and venues, including the Australian Centre for the Moving Image, 2005
> (Melbourne); Centre Pompidou 2004 and 2001, Mus=E9e d'Art Moderne de la V=
ille
> 1999, and La Villette 2002 (all Paris); S=F3nar 1999 and 2006 (Barcelona)=
;
> Architectural Association 2002, Barbican 2006, Hayward Gallery 2000,
> Millennium Dome 2000, Queen Elizabeth Hall 2000, Tate Modern Turbine Hall
> 2006 (all London); Auditorium Parco della Musica 2003 (Rome); ICC 1999 an=
d
> 2005, Tokyo International Forum 2006 (Tokyo); G=F6teborg Biennial 2003
> (G=F6teborg). In 2001, Ikeda was awarded the Ars Electronica Golden Nica =
prize
> in the digital music category and he was short-listed for a World Technol=
ogy

It sounds to me that someone in authority decided that these "homemade 
radios" looked like improvised weapons. I know that's total B.S. -- as if people 
would be dancing when there are more important things to do like tending to the 
weapons -- but that's the excuse. Looking like zombies isn't the purported 
crime here, it's having something that, absurd as it is, looks like an improvised 
weapon. 
I'd just like to see what they're talking about. If they have a boom box 
decorated to look roughly like a weapon, and it says "TO BE DROPPED ON WHITE 
HOUSE," the authorities would have something, although VERY flimsy, to hang on the 
people and use the EXCUSE of this WMD law to hassle the make-believe zombies. 
Even still, there are plenty of laws they could draw on, like laws against 
illegal assembly, lack of permits, amount of noise, complaints from the 
public,etc etc but jeeesus this sure isn't a WMD case. 
Maybe they overheard a zombie say "Whoa dude, this party is da bomb" ???

  I am leaving either Tuesday afternoon or Wednesday morning, and returning to SF on Sunday. I have room for one person's gear and bike. I am looking for someone to share gas and driving. Solitude is nice but on a six-hour drive, lively conversation is preferred.

Free parties return to UK




Police are attempting to stop upcoming 'raves'

Police have reported that free "rave" parties in are on the rise again in the UK.

Officers have explained that they have policed several events in recent weeks and are now attempting to find out the details of one massive, illegal party in particular, which is due to take place in the coming weeks.

Intelligence specialists are monitoring websites and party phonelines attempting to pick up word of further free parties and festivals.

An event, featuring the likes of The <http://www.nme.com/artists/klaxons>Klaxons, in a disused office block in London on July 21 was broken up after just one hour 

Meanwhile Devon And Cornwall police are concerned that ravers will attempt a party in the West Country following a recent event in Newquay that saw partygoers used a car rally as cover for a rave.

Meanwhile, officers in Davidstow near Camelford, watched as 5,000 people hold a party on a disused airfield, while Thames Valley police are using ASBO legislation to crack down on raves, The Guardian reports.

The Conservative government passed The Criminal Justice and Public Act Order in 1994 attempting to thwart the spread of dance culture parties. It gave police the power to tackle "A gathering on land in the open air...at which amplified music is played during the night."

However with the current rise of the new rave scene, it's believed fans are now also resurrecting free party culture. 

http://www.nme.com/news/klaxons/23701

*** TRANCEPORTAL PRESENTS - A DAYTIME TRANCE MUSIC GATHERING ***

The Tranceportal.org Crew and special guest DJs invite you to come to  
a free
outdoor event in Golden Gate Park, San Francisco. We'll be playing  
hours of
high-energy electronic music on Sunday August 13th, 2006 starting at  
noon
until 6pm.

This event is fully permitted and in a beautiful outdoor location  
centrally
located in the city of San Francisco.  You may forward this on to other
lists that might enjoy it.


*** DONATIONS ***

This is a free party, but we will be taking donations in support of our
friend Josh Wolf. Josh is now being held in a federal prison in order to
coerce him to testify and turn over his unpublished video to a  
federal grand
jury.

This event is not a protest or a demonstation, but we will be giving  
100% of
all donations to help Josh Wolf cover his $15,000 in legal expenses.

More information on his situation is at:
http://freejosh.pbwiki.com
http://sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2006/08/01/MNGVQK97AK4.DTL


*** DETAILS ***

Date: Sunday August 13th, 2006
Time: Noon until 6:00pm
Location: Elk Glen Meadow - Golden Gate Park, San Francisco CA


*** WHAT TO BRING ***

There's plenty of shade and sun in the Elk Glen Meadow. You might  
want to
bring some chairs or a blanket to spread out on the grass. There will  
be a
couple of grills available on site that a few of us are bringing,  
feel free
to use them. Alcohol is allowed at Elk Glen Meadow. Please help us  
keep the
space clean and use the provided trash cans.


*** RESTROOMS ***

We will have a single portable toilet on site. Please use it instead  
of the
bushes. The next closest toilets are a 15 minute walk to the Polo  
Fields.


*** LINEUP ***

Noon - 1:00pm Jason Lee [Stargaze]
1:00pm - 2:00pm Ray C [Butterzone / Tranceportal] 2:00pm - 3:00pm Rahul
[Turiyasounds / Outpost23] 3:00pm - 4:00pm gEoff ;) [Stargaze] 4:00pm -
6:00pm Addison/Colin/Paul [Tranceportal / Stargaze]


*** DIRECTIONS ***

- Google directions and get to Lincoln Way at 25th Ave. in Golden  
Gate Park
- San Francisco
- Go north on 25th Ave.
- Left at the T intersectoin onto Martin Luther King Jr. Drive
- Elk Glen Meadow is on your right hand side after a couple hundred feet
- Park anywhere on Martin Luther King Jr. Drive

--
http://www.tranceportal.org






apollo@speakeasy.org

MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo

Tribenet:   http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k

Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm



"No sage or savior has ever endorsed greed and gluttony as a path  
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and  
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras,  
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and  
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can  
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and  
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond  
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative  
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in  
squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of  
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will  
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

http://www.startribune.com/462/story/572409.html

'Zombie dancers' spend their weekend in lockup
Minneapolis police arrested the group on suspicion of having =20
"simulated weapons of mass destruction," but no charges filed.
Chao Xiong, Star Tribune
Last update: July 25, 2006 =96 1:39 AM

Group members assess damage

DAVID JOLES, STAR TRIBUNE

In the middle of downtown Minneapolis Saturday night, police found =20
seven people clustered on a street corner, some pale-faced and =20
covered in fake blood and wearing tattered clothes. A few carried =20
backpacks with protruding wires.
It was, participants said later, a "zombie dance party," in which a =20
group of young friends dress in sometimes outlandish attire and =20
congregate in public places to dance to music from portable stereos =20
carried on their backs.
But when the dancers wouldn't tell police concerned about the =20
mysterious wires, give their names or provide identification, they =20
ended up arrested, held in jail until Monday afternoon on suspicion =20
of having "simulated weapons of mass destruction."
None have been charged.
Police say the group was uncooperative and intimidated passersby with =20=

their "ghoulish" makeup at a time when officers were on high alert in =20=

reaction to a bulletin about men in other states who wear clown =20
makeup while attacking and robbing people, said Inspector Janee Harteau.
"Given the circumstance of them being uncooperative ... why would you =20=

have those [bags] if not to intimidate people?" Harteau said. "It's =20
not a case of [police] overreacting."
Kate Kibby, who was one of those arrested, had a different opinion. =20
She said the group met at the Nicollet Mall light-rail station for a =20
"zombie dance party," which generally occur in public spaces. =20
Sometimes, she said, strangers join in. The parties have occurred =20
without arrest at the Mall of America and on light-rail trains, she =20
said.
The group -- six adults and a juvenile -- had just finished watching =20
a drum line near 6th Street and Hennepin Avenue when two officers =20
approached, asked for identification and refused to say why they were =20=

being questioned, Kibby said. "We should have had an explanation as =20
to why [they wanted our identification] and they weren't giving it to =20=

us," she said.
Christian Utne, one of the event organizers, said that happened about =20=

45 minutes after two different officers approached them on Nicollet =20
Mall and asked them to turn down the volume of their music. Those =20
officers then left the group alone, he said.
"It was absolutely ridiculous," said Utne. "Outrageous."
Kibby, Utne and police agree that group members initially did not =20
reveal their identities. But Kibby said the group -- not knowing what =20=

would happen -- did cooperate and follow the two officers to the =20
First Precinct.
The two original officers didn't appear to think the backpacks were =20
bombs, said Kibby, who said she had a messenger bag. They weren't =20
searched until after they arrived at the First Precinct, where she =20
said several officers appeared to be making fun of them, she said.
Police spokesman Lt. Greg Reinhardt said reports show that there were =20=

"four items that were used to simulate an explosive device."
Members of the group could still face lesser charges, such as =20
disorderly conduct, police said. Kibby said group members are =20
considering legal action.
"It was clear to us that they were trying to get a rise out of us," =20
she said.

Chao Xiong =95 612-673-4391

On 8/7/06, Deepfog <sfgroove@deepfog.com> wrote:
>
> http://www.startribune.com/462/story/572409.html
>
> 'Zombie dancers' spend their weekend in lockup
> Minneapolis police arrested the group on suspicion of having
> "simulated weapons of mass destruction," but no charges filed.
> Chao Xiong, Star Tribune
> Last update: July 25, 2006 =96 1:39 AM
>
> Group members assess damage
>
> DAVID JOLES, STAR TRIBUNE
>
> In the middle of downtown Minneapolis Saturday night, police found
> seven people clustered on a street corner, some pale-faced and
> covered in fake blood and wearing tattered clothes. A few carried
> backpacks with protruding wires.
> It was, participants said later, a "zombie dance party," in which a
> group of young friends dress in sometimes outlandish attire and
> congregate in public places to dance to music from portable stereos
> carried on their backs.
> But when the dancers wouldn't tell police concerned about the
> mysterious wires, give their names or provide identification, they
> ended up arrested, held in jail until Monday afternoon on suspicion
> of having "simulated weapons of mass destruction."
> None have been charged.
> Police say the group was uncooperative and intimidated passersby with
> their "ghoulish" makeup at a time when officers were on high alert in
> reaction to a bulletin about men in other states who wear clown
> makeup while attacking and robbing people, said Inspector Janee Harteau.
> "Given the circumstance of them being uncooperative ... why would you
> have those [bags] if not to intimidate people?" Harteau said. "It's
> not a case of [police] overreacting."
> Kate Kibby, who was one of those arrested, had a different opinion.
> She said the group met at the Nicollet Mall light-rail station for a
> "zombie dance party," which generally occur in public spaces.
> Sometimes, she said, strangers join in. The parties have occurred
> without arrest at the Mall of America and on light-rail trains, she
> said.
> The group -- six adults and a juvenile -- had just finished watching
> a drum line near 6th Street and Hennepin Avenue when two officers
> approached, asked for identification and refused to say why they were
> being questioned, Kibby said. "We should have had an explanation as
> to why [they wanted our identification] and they weren't giving it to
> us," she said.
> Christian Utne, one of the event organizers, said that happened about
> 45 minutes after two different officers approached them on Nicollet
> Mall and asked them to turn down the volume of their music. Those
> officers then left the group alone, he said.
> "It was absolutely ridiculous," said Utne. "Outrageous."
> Kibby, Utne and police agree that group members initially did not
> reveal their identities. But Kibby said the group -- not knowing what
> would happen -- did cooperate and follow the two officers to the
> First Precinct.
> The two original officers didn't appear to think the backpacks were
> bombs, said Kibby, who said she had a messenger bag. They weren't
> searched until after they arrived at the First Precinct, where she
> said several officers appeared to be making fun of them, she said.
> Police spokesman Lt. Greg Reinhardt said reports show that there were
> "four items that were used to simulate an explosive device."
> Members of the group could still face lesser charges, such as
> disorderly conduct, police said. Kibby said group members are
> considering legal action.
> "It was clear to us that they were trying to get a rise out of us,"
> she said.
>

Sorry.  Grew up up there.  Don't get your hopes up.

Santa Rosa and most of SoCo considers the RAVE Act to be one of the books 
of the New Testament.  I rememeber in the arly 90s there were a few Raves 
out in the river area and the spin the media they put on them made'em sound 
like they were worse than some satanic cult gathering to slaughter 
animimals.  Like doing a little N2O was far worse than shooting Heroin in a 
dirty alley somewhere.

I was throwing some stuff in '99 up there in some unincorporated area.  We 
hbarred some undesireables from coming in so they calle dthe cops and told 
them that there were naked peopel running around.  We had the entire 
Sheriff dept show up that night, 25 cars plus 3 K-9 units.  This wasn't 
even a "Rave" just a party with about 200 ppl (ya ok, loud music, full open 
bar, and lot of wacky fetish people in PVC and Latex getting freaky in all 
areas of the house.  I think it might have been Liquid Latex 
night...   memory is cloudy).

Subject: [sfraves] Ketamine rapidly lifts depression

Well, I'm ready to take off......

Anesthesia Drug Rapidly Lifts Depression, Researchers Say


By Amanda Gardner

HealthDay Reporter 1 hour, 18 minutes ago

MONDAY, Aug. 7 (HealthDay News) -- A single dose of an anesthesia  
drug produced relief from depression in as little as two hours in a  
small group of patients for whom several other treatments had failed,  
U.S. government researchers report.

The researchers said, however, that the drug, ketamine, is unlikely  
to be used in the treatment of depression because of possible side  
effects, including psychosis. But the new finding does signal an  
important direction for future research.

Currently available antidepressants can take weeks to work. "That was  
similar to the sound barrier. We felt we couldn't pass it," said Dr.  
Carlos A. Zarate Jr., lead author of the study and chief of the mood  
disorders research unit at the National Institute of Mental Health.

He added, "Now the sound barrier is broken. That doesn't mean you can  
get on the plane and take off right away, but it means it's possible  
that we can come up with a treatment that works very rapidly. That's  
down the road."

Ketamine is novel not only for the speed of its effect, but also  
because it targets a new system in the brain.
"It's novel because all antidepressants that are currently available  
work on neurotransmitters that are monoamines like dopamine and  
serotonin. That's the focus of the current antidepressant  
armamentarium," explained Dr. Richard A. Friedman, director of the  
psychopharmacology clinic at Cornell University's Medical Center in  
New York City. "Ketamine involves a particular system of the brain  
called glutamate. It's the main excitory neurotransmitter in the  
brain," he said.

Depression is a chronic, disabling condition affecting almost 15  
million Americans -- almost 7 percent of the adult U.S. population --  
in any given year. Some 4 percent of people with depression will end  
their own lives, resulting in 30,000 suicides each year.

Unfortunately, about half of people with depression don't receive  
treatment and, of those who do get treatment, only about 40 percent  
get the best, "evidence-based" treatment. Some people still don't get  
better even with this type of treatment, however.
This is one of the first studies in humans to look at the effect of  
ketamine on depression, although previous animal studies had shown  
promising results.
For the study, which is published in the August issue of the Archives  
of General Psychiatry, 18 treatment-resistant patients with  
depression were randomly assigned to receive either one intravenous  
dose of ketamine or a placebo. Participants had tried an average of  
six antidepressant medications without success in the past.
Depression improved within one day in 71 percent of participants who  
received ketamine; 29 percent of those became nearly symptom-free  
within one day. Thirty-five percent of those receiving ketamine still  
showed benefits after several weeks. Those in the placebo group  
showed no improvement.

One week later, participants were given the opposite treatment,  
unless they were still showing a benefit from the ketamine.

"People had tried six to seven antidepressants on average and had  
been ill for 30 years. The current episode was three years in  
duration," Zarate said. "All people who went through this reported a  
tremendous relief of suffering."

Short-term side effects, including perception disturbances, went away  
usually before the antidepressant effect kicked in. Participants were  
given a relatively low dose, so they did not experience the more  
severe side effects.

Ketamine works by blocking the N-methyl-D-aspartic acid (NMDA)  
receptor, which receives signals for glutamate. Using ketamine to  
block glutamate's action on the NMDA receptor also seemed to have a  
secondary effect on another brain receptor, the AMPA receptor.

Zarate and his team are now looking at several ways to use this  
information for depressed patients. "We're looking to see if we can  
refine ketamine for clinical use by taking care of side effects," he  
said. "We're also looking at other drugs."
--Apple-Mail-1-594554618--

On 8/7/06, Apollo <apollo@speakeasy.org> wrote:
>
> Well, I'm ready to take off......
>
> Anesthesia Drug Rapidly Lifts Depression, Researchers Say
>
>
> By Amanda Gardner
>
> HealthDay Reporter 1 hour, 18 minutes ago
>
> MONDAY, Aug. 7 (HealthDay News) -- A single dose of an anesthesia
> drug produced relief from depression in as little as two hours in a
> small group of patients for whom several other treatments had failed,
> U.S. government researchers report.
>
> The researchers said, however, that the drug, ketamine, is unlikely
> to be used in the treatment of depression because of possible side
> effects, including psychosis. But the new finding does signal an
> important direction for future research.
>
> Currently available antidepressants can take weeks to work. "That was
> similar to the sound barrier. We felt we couldn't pass it," said Dr.
> Carlos A. Zarate Jr., lead author of the study and chief of the mood
> disorders research unit at the National Institute of Mental Health.
>
> He added, "Now the sound barrier is broken. That doesn't mean you can
> get on the plane and take off right away, but it means it's possible
> that we can come up with a treatment that works very rapidly. That's
> down the road."
>
> Ketamine is novel not only for the speed of its effect, but also
> because it targets a new system in the brain.
> "It's novel because all antidepressants that are currently available
> work on neurotransmitters that are monoamines like dopamine and
> serotonin. That's the focus of the current antidepressant
> armamentarium," explained Dr. Richard A. Friedman, director of the
> psychopharmacology clinic at Cornell University's Medical Center in
> New York City. "Ketamine involves a particular system of the brain
> called glutamate. It's the main excitory neurotransmitter in the
> brain," he said.
>
> Depression is a chronic, disabling condition affecting almost 15
> million Americans -- almost 7 percent of the adult U.S. population --
> in any given year. Some 4 percent of people with depression will end
> their own lives, resulting in 30,000 suicides each year.
>
> Unfortunately, about half of people with depression don't receive
> treatment and, of those who do get treatment, only about 40 percent
> get the best, "evidence-based" treatment. Some people still don't get
> better even with this type of treatment, however.
> This is one of the first studies in humans to look at the effect of
> ketamine on depression, although previous animal studies had shown
> promising results.
> For the study, which is published in the August issue of the Archives
> of General Psychiatry, 18 treatment-resistant patients with
> depression were randomly assigned to receive either one intravenous
> dose of ketamine or a placebo. Participants had tried an average of
> six antidepressant medications without success in the past.
> Depression improved within one day in 71 percent of participants who
> received ketamine; 29 percent of those became nearly symptom-free
> within one day. Thirty-five percent of those receiving ketamine still
> showed benefits after several weeks. Those in the placebo group
> showed no improvement.
>
> One week later, participants were given the opposite treatment,
> unless they were still showing a benefit from the ketamine.
>
> "People had tried six to seven antidepressants on average and had
> been ill for 30 years. The current episode was three years in
> duration," Zarate said. "All people who went through this reported a
> tremendous relief of suffering."
>
> Short-term side effects, including perception disturbances, went away
> usually before the antidepressant effect kicked in. Participants were
> given a relatively low dose, so they did not experience the more
> severe side effects.
>
> Ketamine works by blocking the N-methyl-D-aspartic acid (NMDA)
> receptor, which receives signals for glutamate. Using ketamine to
> block glutamate's action on the NMDA receptor also seemed to have a
> secondary effect on another brain receptor, the AMPA receptor.
>
> Zarate and his team are now looking at several ways to use this
> information for depressed patients. "We're looking to see if we can
> refine ketamine for clinical use by taking care of side effects," he
> said. "We're also looking at other drugs."
>



-- 
Steve Osteen is SlumberMachine
http://www.SlumberMachine.com

running with it as hard as we can. And we just couldn't resist the name 
"Crooked," knowing the way things usually get at Nickie's.

1.2") will be holding it down, bringing in very special guests from around 
the Bay and beyond every week. We go from 10pm 'til 2am at Nickie's, and, 
unfortunately, we can't keep the free door hook-ups that we used to have at 
@lpha - we've got to charge $3 at the door at Crooked. But come on, $3... 
that's less than the cost of a drink! And well worth it for the lineups we

>From: "Van Mundegaarde" <electrofunk138@hotmail.com>

>Date: Tue, 08 Aug 2006 10:55:34 -0700
>
>Yes yes! The time has come to move to a venue a little more our speed: 
>Darker, dirtier, grittier, louder, closer into the center of everything. 
>Nickie's on Lower Haight is just the spot, and I've been eyeing it up and 
>down for a while. So we snatched up Wednesdays really quickly, and we're 
>running with it as hard as we can. And we just couldn't resist the name 
>"Crooked," knowing the way things usually get at Nickie's.
>
>m.d.K, Erok, Evinrude and I (the newly formed "Renegade Ferrets version 
>1.2") will be holding it down, bringing in very special guests from around 
>the Bay and beyond every week. We go from 10pm 'til 2am at Nickie's, and, 
>unfortunately, we can't keep the free door hook-ups that we used to have at 
>@lpha - we've got to charge $3 at the door at Crooked. But come on, $3... 
>that's less than the cost of a drink! And well worth it for the lineups we 
>plan to put together on a weekly basis.
>
>For our premiere show, this week, August 9th, we're gonna kick it off with 
>a lineup that's a bit of a preview of the type of night we want this to be 
>every time (with an admitted bit of overkill on the numbers, since this 
>one's special) - a few of our favorites all coming together for one wicked 
>night of breaks:
>
>
>8.9.06:
>Kapt'n Kirk
>Ernie Trevino
>Ripple
>Satsi
>Evinrude
>
>So come out, have a drink with us, say hello, and help us usher in Crooked, 
>a brand-new way to do Wednesday nights.
>
>Oh yeah, I almost forgot:
>
>GET BENT!!!
>
>8.16.06 lineup:

>Thomas Kent

>Marc(O)

I was going to write something similiar to that myself, but was waiting on a concensus. Yeah, teach him about free thumb galleries & P2P. No need for the credit card to get maxed out just yet!
   
  On a more serious note, sounds like you're turning to this list for help. If your son is capable of utilizing a wireless router, I think the only thing any content filter would do is develop his hacking skills. If it's an issue, you can always unplug the router at night if it's outside of his room- but more importantly- perhaps it's about that time for the 'talk. Don't try to dictate anything to him, just ask if he has any questions or find a dude that he trusts to rap with him. Tell him that he's normal to be curious and not to feel shy about it, but at the same time there's a "time & place" for such subject matter just like dirty jokes or cuss words. What's important is that he learns not to embarrass himself and all will be well. Sometimes kids like to feel like adults, so if you teach him that it's an adult thing and how adults handle it, maybe he'll run with it. Hope that helps, I'm just guessing at this shit. 
   
  I wish my parents were on SFR. 
   
  Best, 
   
  Chuck

Subject: Re: [sfraves] nrr: interweb babysitter

Um, I think about this stuff all the time, as I see
billboards and adds for sex any time I move 10 feet in
Las Vegas.

It is innapropriate for a boy to see porn and sex at
his age. If he is to grow up with a normal view of
sexual relationships with women as well as a general
respect for women, block the porn with whatever
resources you can manage. Best of all, talk to him
about it, make him face it, make him see how
uncomfortable he is with it around you as his mother.
My therapist years ago told me that mothers, as mine
did, often abruptly lose touch with their sons at age
12 -13, because they don't know how to approach and
deal with their emerging sexuality.

This being said, I remember all my first sexual
experiences, the uncomfortableness of touching a girls
"boob," trying to "get down her pants," etc.... I had
no idea what I was looking for, what it would feel
like, and was often in awe or confused, or over
stimulated, etc.... ANd... so was she.

Point being, letting your 12 yr old get all the info
without going through the experimentation is like
handing a kid a speech to text converter and never
teaching them to write or spell...

Most important... to much porn to a 12 yr old breeds
bizarre expectations, dissociative sexual habits, and
probably leads to an increased chance of date rape in
the future. That being said, there is a HUGE
difference between seeing a naked woman in playboy,
and watching people FUCK.

My TWO cents.

Eric
