I agree with Eric, I don't see any need for a 13 year old to be watching
hard core nrop and without a proper father figure showing how to properly
treat and respect women this could be a big cause of concern. I say check
out his history folder (or cache folder if he is savvy enough to clear the
history folder) and see exactly where he is going, then make a list of the
domain names. You can then go into your router and ban all the domains (like
www.whenharrywetsally.com). If you have a linksys router you can access it
by typing in http://192.168.1.1/ on a connected computer.
Also, is it possible to place the computer in a easily seen place, like the
family room? and Limit the time allowed.

I don't let my son use the internet unless I'm in the same room and made a
firm rule that he must tell me before he does any google searches for
anything.

Good luck!



On 8/10/06, Eric Spire <ericspire@yahoo.com> wrote:
>
> Um, I think about this stuff all the time, as I see
> billboards and adds for sex any time I move 10 feet in
> Las Vegas.
>
> It is innapropriate for a boy to see porn and sex at
> his age. If he is to grow up with a normal view of
> sexual relationships with women as well as a general
> respect for women, block the porn with whatever
> resources you can manage. Best of all, talk to him
> about it, make him face it, make him see how
> uncomfortable he is with it around you as his mother.
> My therapist years ago told me that mothers, as mine
> did, often abruptly lose touch with their sons at age
> 12 -13, because they don't know how to approach and
> deal with their emerging sexuality.
>
> This being said, I remember all my first sexual
> experiences, the uncomfortableness of touching a girls
> "boob," trying to "get down her pants," etc.... I had
> no idea what I was looking for, what it would feel
> like, and was often in awe or confused, or over
> stimulated, etc.... ANd... so was she.
>
> Point being, letting your 12 yr old get all the info
> without going through the experimentation is like
> handing a kid a speech to text converter and never
> teaching them to write or spell...
>
> Most important... to much porn to a 12 yr old breeds
> bizarre expectations, dissociative sexual habits, and
> probably leads to an increased chance of date rape in
> the future. That being said, there is a HUGE
> difference between seeing a naked woman in playboy,
> and watching people FUCK.
>
> My TWO cents.
>
> Eric

Subject: [sfraves] High level alert over rave rebirth

--=====================_20790265==.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"

High level alert over rave rebirth
By <mailto:krussell@london.newsquest.co.uk>Kate Russell

by RUBY ALI Landowners in Enfield have been warned to keep their property secure in the wake of the re-emergence of the illegal rave scene.

The warning has been issued by Enfield Council which is supporting a nationwide police operation to track and prevent illegal raves across the UK.

Illegal raves had their heyday in the 1980s and 1990s, typifying the drugs and dance culture of the time, where big warehouses would be used to hold illegal all-night parties.

The last illegal rave in Enfield was held in September 2002, when an empty warehouse in Lockfield Avenue was taken over and hundreds of residents were disturbed by the noise which could be heard as far away as Waltham Cross.

It is thought the resurgance in the illegal rave is due to stricter controls on the use of drugs in nightclubs (1). It is also being seen as a reaction to chav (2) culture' that is overtaking the club scene.

Assistant director of the environment Ray Brewer said: "We have not been troubled by raves in the recent past. On the last occasion an industrial site was taken over due to insufficient security.

"We have no specific intelligence but we do advise owners of large sites to check the security of their property and remain vigilant to unusual activity.

"The police and local authority have powers to take enforcement action and prosecution, but prevention is always better than cure."

The rave scene died out after legislation brought in by the Conservative Government in 1994 gave police greater powers of arrest and banned open-air gatherings on land where amplified music was played during the night. The scene was also associated with the drug ecstasy.

5:42pm Wednesday 9th August 2006

http://www.enfieldindependent.co.uk/news/localnews/display.var.871144.0.high_level_alert_over_rave_rebirth.php


My notes:

(1)
Perhaps they are sick of the booze culture and the nauseating music and vibe it generates.

(2)  
Chav (also Chavette (female chav)) is a <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slang>slang term in wide use throughout the <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Kingdom>United Kingdom since <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2004>2004.
It refers to a <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Subculture>subcultural <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stereotype>stereotype of people fixated on <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fashion>fashions such as flashy "<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bling>bling" jewelery, and genuine or knock-off designer clothing with the beige <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Burberry>Burberry pattern (most famously the <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baseball_cap>baseball cap which has since been discontinued by the company), and such brands as <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adidas>Adidas and <http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nike%2C_Inc.>Nike and Lacoste.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] nrr: interweb babysitter

on a slightly different tangent:

this might seem strange to some, but right around that age my mom did
something to demystify sex:

she bought me some of the most scientifically and graphically explicit
books on sexual functions and the human body.  full color diagrams and
cross sections of the penis, uterus, vagina and all that good stuff.
you remember those books you had as a kid with the little "pull here"
tabs and dials and switches?  these books had that too.  pull the
lever and see the sperm swim into the fallopian tubes!  turn and dial
and watch the color of the testes change!

like any kid, i was curious about sex and any porn i got my hands on
was a godsend.  but i always remembered those books and sex didn't
seem like this strange and mystical thing that was super taboo.

*shrug*

Thats just brought up some funny memories... 

"Where did I come from" and "whats happening to
me"....

Those were the books I was given by mom as the "sex
talk."

My inept father's version of the sex talk...
"Do you have hair in your groin?" and "As you get
older, men need to where deodorant."

The books my mom gave me, along with sneak peaks at
the "joy of sex" were the training I got. I never saw
porn until I was an adult... unless the occasional
peak at playboy and national geographic count.

--- Bam <invibe@gmail.com> wrote:

> on a slightly different tangent:
> 
> this might seem strange to some, but right around
> that age my mom did
> something to demystify sex:
> 
> she bought me some of the most scientifically and
> graphically explicit
> books on sexual functions and the human body.  full
> color diagrams and
> cross sections of the penis, uterus, vagina and all
> that good stuff.
> you remember those books you had as a kid with the
> little "pull here"
> tabs and dials and switches?  these books had that
> too.  pull the
> lever and see the sperm swim into the fallopian
> tubes!  turn and dial
> and watch the color of the testes change!
> 
> like any kid, i was curious about sex and any porn i
> got my hands on
> was a godsend.  but i always remembered those books
> and sex didn't
> seem like this strange and mystical thing that was
> super taboo.
> 
> *shrug*

> On 8/10/06, Steve Osteen <sosteen@gmail.com> wrote:

> > I agree with Eric, I don't see any need for a 13
> year old to be watching
> > hard core nrop and without a proper father figure
> showing how to properly
> > treat and respect women this could be a big cause
> of concern. I say check
> > out his history folder (or cache folder if he is
> savvy enough to clear the
> > history folder) and see exactly where he is going,
> then make a list of the
> > domain names. You can then go into your router and
> ban all the domains (like
> > www.whenharrywetsally.com). If you have a linksys
> router you can access it
> > by typing in http://192.168.1.1/ on a connected
> computer.
> > Also, is it possible to place the computer in a
> easily seen place, like the
> > family room? and Limit the time allowed.
> >

> the same room and made a
> > firm rule that he must tell me before he does any

> > anything.

on a slightly different tangent:

this might seem strange to some, but right around that age my mom did
something to demystify sex:

she bought me some of the most scientifically and graphically explicit
books on sexual functions and the human body.  full color diagrams and
cross sections of the penis, uterus, vagina and all that good stuff.
you remember those books you had as a kid with the little "pull here"
tabs and dials and switches?  these books had that too.  pull the
lever and see the sperm swim into the fallopian tubes!  turn and dial
and watch the color of the testes change!

like any kid, i was curious about sex and any porn i got my hands on
was a godsend.  but i always remembered those books and sex didn't
seem like this strange and mystical thing that was super taboo.

*shrug*


On 8/10/06, Steve Osteen <sosteen@gmail.com> wrote:
> Adriana,
>
> I agree with Eric, I don't see any need for a 13 year old to be watching
> hard core nrop and without a proper father figure showing how to properly
> treat and respect women this could be a big cause of concern. I say check
> out his history folder (or cache folder if he is savvy enough to clear the
> history folder) and see exactly where he is going, then make a list of the
> domain names. You can then go into your router and ban all the domains (like
> www.whenharrywetsally.com). If you have a linksys router you can access it
> by typing in http://192.168.1.1/ on a connected computer.
> Also, is it possible to place the computer in a easily seen place, like the
> family room? and Limit the time allowed.
>
> I don't let my son use the internet unless I'm in the same room and made a
> firm rule that he must tell me before he does any google searches for
> anything.
>
> Good luck!
>
>
>
> On 8/10/06, Eric Spire <ericspire@yahoo.com> wrote:

> > Um, I think about this stuff all the time, as I see

> > Las Vegas.

> > It is innapropriate for a boy to see porn and sex at
> > his age. If he is to grow up with a normal view of
> > sexual relationships with women as well as a general
> > respect for women, block the porn with whatever
> > resources you can manage. Best of all, talk to him
> > about it, make him face it, make him see how
> > uncomfortable he is with it around you as his mother.
> > My therapist years ago told me that mothers, as mine
> > did, often abruptly lose touch with their sons at age
> > 12 -13, because they don't know how to approach and
> > deal with their emerging sexuality.
> >

> > experiences, the uncomfortableness of touching a girls

> > like, and was often in awe or confused, or over
> > stimulated, etc.... ANd... so was she.

> > without going through the experimentation is like

Subject: Re: [sfraves] The rave scene and what it's all about?

I think to be into that sort of music is one thing,
but 'rave' is a very specific term, with modern
connotations that the experience is made more exciting
via intoxicants. It's like, if you're going to a bar
you're probably going to drink some alcohol. Does that
mean you only love alcohol and the bar isn't about
hanging out with your friends and meeting people as
well?

Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1; format=flowed
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit

You're right about that. Generally rave = loud repetitive music + 
ectsasy (and about 50 other different chems). Old scruffy rave heads 
like the ones on this list don't like to talk about how important drugs 
are to the scene, but they are indeed very important.

Anyway, I'd recommend checking out groundscore.net and perusing the 
forums there for parties that look interesting. And, basically, just go 
out and meet people until you find a group of people that you like 
hanging out with. The rest of the culture will reveal itself eventually. :-)

To me the rave scene is about the music, its about the people. Would a rave be a rave without the music? Would a rave be a rave without the people? Some of yall might feel that its about the drugs and thats cool. Whatever works for you. Iv been partying since 99, Iv been going to partys to celebrate the music. To celebrate the peace, the love, the unity and the respect we have for one another................

I'll state the obvious from everyone's point of view:

You're a cop.

Not only are you a cop, you're a poorly trained cop. You don't show up
on the premier San Francisco rave mailing list, and as your inaugural
post, discuss drugs and their usage. That's both stupid and moronic.

If you aren't a cop, your views of the rave scene have been obviously
skewed by the likes of Paul Van Dyk, Tiesto, and Keoki. There IS a
rave scene without drugs, and there are those who also like doing
drugs (which I personally don't partake in) generally do it behind
closed doors, and don't publicly speak of it, as it is a private event
in their lives.

Please, don't be offended by this. I'm only calling this as I see it.

Regards,

On 8/11/06, Justin Johnson <justinsuperstar@yahoo.com> wrote:

> mean you only love alcohol and the bar isn't about
> hanging out with your friends and meeting people as
> well?
>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] The rave scene and what it's all about?

Are you for real?

I'm certain my views are fucked up, because I've never
actually BEEN to a rave. I just moved here from
Orlando, which really doesn't have much happening,
aside from the occasional Disney parade, and was just
interested in meeting some new people.

The first thing that pops into people's mind when a
'rave' is mentioned, is loud techno dance music,
dancing sweaty kids wearing obnoxious neon-colored
clothing, and ecstasy. So I wouldn't consider it so
freakishly out of the ordinary for me to mention such
a thing. I'm not aware of how huge this list is, it
seemed like a nice, tight-knit community that I wanted
to participate in.

You can claim it's deeper from your obviously more
experienced viewpoint. We don't all have that. It's
something I wouldn't mind earning, but if I'm going to
get gangfucked by the old guard, that doesn't sound so
pleasant. 

Where's the friggin' LOVE?

Since this started with an inquiry about parties...I remember this thread
from 06/27/06 - I hope AndyW doesn't mind me re-posting this, because I
think it sums up partying/raving really well.  The original discussion was
clubs vs undergrounds...




On 6/27/06, AndyW <andy@saturn5.com> wrote:

>
> On Mon, 26 Jun 2006, Apollo wrote:
> -&e->Raves began here when, amongst other irritations, the communal dance
> folks
> -&e->got tired of the clubs.  Raves ended when those involved saw
> opportunities
> -&e->to make bucks...like the clubs.  My partner collected boxes of old
> fliers
> -&e->from late eighties early nineties SF underground gay and mixed
> parties we
> -&e->used to attend.  All of them were hand written and run off on color
> papers.
> -&e->Some were stickers one would paste on one's black motorcycle
> jacket:)  Then
> -&e->came the late nineties.  Four color fliers.  BIG.
>
> Bingo to Apollo for stating the obvious yet not often enough said.
>
> These events are gatherings, where the promoter, the DJ and the attendee
> melted away and all became participants.  Where the rules and societal
> mores gave way to a simpler ethic, one that embraced personal freedoms,
> and a result that at worst was a lame night out, at best was a life
> changing experience.  So many nights were I came with $5 to get in and
> that's all I worried about, walking home in the san francisco morning
> light aware, in love, bulletproof.  Other nights where I brought sound.
> Other nights where I shared music.  Mornings where people would offer to
> carry my records, not because I was a DJ, but because they looked heavy.
> Afterparties where we fell asleep on each other and woke up to the same DJ
> playing Brian Eno 8 hours later.  Bringing fruit to parties and just
> handing it out in the chill room.  The communal wail of one person yelling
> in joy and having everybody else join in, we became rays shooting out of a
> sun nobody could see but all knew was there.  Tangible energy arcing
> across the sky, the future promising if only because it might be 1% of the
> way we felt right then.  We took such good care of each other and some of
> us still do.
>
> The opposite of a proper rave or underground gathering is the VIP club.
> I don't even want to fucking hear about it.  Take your velvet ropes and
> shove them up your ass, and with gusto.  For them to have value it means
> people coming out and being told "no, you're not good enough".  Not what I
> signed up for, not at all.  I don't care what the criteria is... if it's
> who you know, what color your skin is, how much dick you suck or how much
> money you appear to have... it's fucking retarded.  The world needs
> another stuck up club full of hair product guidos and platinum sluts with
> mouths like groupers like I need a hernia.
>
> Take your fucking SUV driving, platinum money clip lying to get laid ass
> and get the fuck out of here.  You're the opposite of getting it, we built
> this in spite of you because we wanted the music, and the dancing and the
> synergy of human energies without all that shit.  You broke rock, you
> broke disco, you break everything you touch, you are dead cities and
> capitalism and face lifts and dishonesty and fear personified.
>
> I want to dance with the ugly people, the poor people, the outsiders, the
> freaks, the nerds, the new kids in town, the people who don't know the
> right people people.  I don't want to enjoy my obviously overpriced bottle
> of what have you in the vip lounge, I want my ass kicked by music, mind
> ripped by intensity, and if I meet some friends for life hell yeah.  I
> prefer big brains to gold chains and I prefer it when the beat is greater
> than the ego.  Make me beg at a velvet rope, search my body for shit that
> is mine, and call me a VIP?  I'm a man who doesn't buy that shit for a
> minute, fuck off.  The only service that shit provides the world is taxing
> the stupid, you're all fucked in the head.
>
> andyw
>
>

On 8/11/06, Philip.X.Diaz <st_indigo@earthlink.net> wrote:

Subject: Re: [sfraves] The rave scene and what it's all about?

Oh snap!  I think I like the new kid!  I've been feeling pretty bitter and
jaded lately and for me I've always been one who likes going to parties
for the music and the energy it provides so I'll take a different route
with this email since those topics have been covered.

I think we're is misinterpreting Justin here.  He's new, he's done the
drugs, he's sitting at home, he and his girl want to expierience new
things and in a few replies we've made him feel like he shouldn't go out,
he should continue to stay at home and not explore all SF and the Bay Area
has to offer for what we on this list love it for.  Electronic music,
freedom of expression and striving for a better community.

So Justin, as far as electronic music goes, are there already styles you
like?  Does the idea of small parties with a typically close knit group of
people interest you or do you wanna go to huge overdone parties with tons
of international talent, local talent, circus clowns, fireworks and jungle
gyms. Would you feel more comfortable in a dance club or parking your car,
hopping in the back of a shuttle bus with a bunch of people you don't
know, then getting dropped off at some place, tromping through a forest
then find a party in the middle of nowhere.

This list is old as time itself almost, those that have been around for a
long time have come to be wary of anything dealing with open discussion
about drugs due to the bad press the electronic music scene has gotten
because of them.  Not to mention these things are of course watched by law
enforcement due to its longevity and because of how well known it is now.

As far as rave, doesn't everyone on this list call them parties now
because of Justin's description of what the term rave has come to mean? ;)

-Rayn

1. Creativity and innovation always builds on the past.
2. The past always tries to control the creativity that builds on it.
3. Free societies enable the future by living in the past.
4. Ours is a less and less a free society.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] nrr: interweb babysitter


By age 13 I had written a war dialer, kept a file of unidentified modems 
locally in an encrypted file that I'd pick off when I was bored, was a 
member on several notorious BBSs, had written 6502 assembler routines so 
my Apple's tape out could record a full compliment of various c-drop tones 
(that I then carried around on a portable cassette tape player in my 
backpack, yay free long distance and phone booths that only cost the first 
nickel) and had copies of the Anarchist's Cookbook and the Army's 
Improvised Field Munitions Manual.

And all in all I had *great* parents.

Your son is getting to the age where it's important to talk to him like a 
young man, not a liability.  His mind is about as powerful as yours now, 
it's just wisdom he lacks.  Oh, and his bloodstream is inundated with with 
a hormone(drug) that has caused more violence and death than religion.  I 
think one of the most vulgar things about our society is the way we treat 
the young and old, sectioning ourselves off into "generations" and 
discarding the wisdom of the old and the energy and alternative viewpoints 
of the young.

If you don't want him seeing that stuff, you will fail.  If you can find a 
way to talk to him about how that industry is all sorts of whack, and how 
women in the real world aren't necessarily into that (most aren't honestly 
into getting choked, fired upon by the milk of 20 businessmen or double 
anal, etc), you might get a better result.  Tell him you don't want to see 
it or find it, and hammer home the real ethics of respect.  Honesty will 
do more for your relationship with him than control.  A 13 year old dude 
is gonna wanna see boobies, welcome to earth.  You don't get to pick who 
he is gonna be, but you can stay with him thru the process of getting 
there.

And yeah, if you try to install all this crap whackware, you'll just teach 
him to cherish porn more, and he'll probably grow up to be a 
sysadmin/network engineer/scary pervert/ghettotech dj.

<3,
andyw

p.s. I don't envy being where you are, can't be easy.  I was a holy 
frikking terror between about 13 to um... still I guess and I am scared to 
death that this is genetic.  In fact, I think I'll go get a vasectomy now.  
C-ya!

andyw - mutorsoundsystem - saturn5.com/andy

Subject: Re: [sfraves] The rave scene and what it's all about?

i'm 25, and without having counted, i'll say i've been to 20-30
raves/parties/spiritual gatherings in the bay area in the past year
and a half.

sometimes i spill my guts to strangers, sometimes i say nothing all
night. sometimes i dance, sometimes i sit against the wall. sometimes
i do drugs, sometimes i don't. usually i lose myself in the music,
sometimes i don't. but i always cast off my day-to-day concerns about
mailing the rent check by the 3rd and, am i out of fabric softener? i
really should get more fabric softener.

what these nights (and sunrises) are about, to me, is the energy and
community. on the subway on weekday mornings, for example, everybody
seems insular and disinterested. but at parties--these kinds of
parties--people run around smiling. you can put your hand on anyone's
shoulder and say, "haha, look at all this; this is crazy!" and yeah, i
like when someone with huge pupils tells me something that they never
even felt comfortable thinking about.

i really believe that in these environments, we release some
intangible essence of ourselves. some call it the "vibe". whether i'm
dancing or just sitting in the corner alone, i'm trying to take in
that vibe, that energy and broadcast my own. that's why i go: to
connect.

also--and i'm not being wry when i say this--i like being in a crowd
that's not drunk.

i'm a quiet guy, i spend most of my time alone, but a rave is just
about the only place i feel comfortable in a room full of people. they
are chances to step outside myself and, you know, just fill up a dozen
water bottles, hand them out to strangers and say, "hi, i usually keep
to myself, but..."

- bobby
http://bobbyburgess.net/journal/

Subject: [sfraves] Sun Aug. 13 - Golden Gate Park - Tranceportal Day Party

Hi everybody!  We're ready to converge on Golden Gate Park tomorrow from
Noon till 6pm.  The weather looks like it's gonna be 
great, come on down and join us!!!   

Here's the info:

-------------------------

*** TRANCEPORTAL PRESENTS - A DAYTIME TRANCE GATHERING ***

The Tranceportal.org Crew and special guest DJs invite you to come to a free
outdoor event in Golden Gate Park, San Francisco. We'll be playing hours of
trance on Sunday August 13th, 2006 starting at noon until 6pm. 

This event is fully permitted and in a beautiful outdoor location centrally
located in the city of San Francisco.

*** DONATIONS ***

This is a free party, but we will be taking donations in support of our
friend Josh Wolf. Josh is now being held in a federal prison in order to
coerce him to testify and turn over his unpublished video to a federal grand
jury.

This event is not a protest or a demonstation, but we will be giving 100% of
all donations to help Josh Wolf cover his $15,000 in legal expenses. 

More information on his situation is at:
http://freejosh.pbwiki.com
http://tinyurl.com/ooldh

*** DETAILS ***

Date: Sunday August 13th, 2006
Time: Noon until 6:00pm
Location: Elk Glen Meadow - Golden Gate Park, San Francisco CA 
Info Page: http://www.tranceportal.org/events/events.htm

*** WHAT TO BRING ***

There's plenty of shade and sun in the Elk Glen Meadow. You might want to
bring some chairs or a blanket to spread out on the grass.  There will be a
couple of grills available on site that a few of us are bringing, feel free
to use them. Alcohol is allowed at Elk Glen Meadow. Please help us keep the
space clean and use the provided trash cans.

*** RESTROOMS ***

We will have a single portable toilet on site. Please use it instead of the
bushes. The next closest toilets are a 15 minute walk to the Polo Fields. 

*** LINEUP ***

Noon - 1:00pm Jason Lee [Stargaze]
1:00pm - 2:00pm Ray C [Butterzone / Tranceportal]
2:00pm - 3:00pm Sanyama [Turiya Sounds / Outpost 23]
3:00pm - 4:00pm gEoff ;) [Stargaze]
4:00pm - 6:00pm Addison/Colin/Paul [Tranceportal / Stargaze]

*** DIRECTIONS ***

- Get to Lincoln Way at 25th Ave. in Golden Gate Park - San Francisco
- Go north on 25th Ave.
- Left at the T intersectoin onto Martin Luther King Jr. Drive
- Elk Glen Meadow is on your hand side after a couple hundred feet
- Park anywhere on Martin Luther King Jr. Drive

Tenchi at the gate and low lighting outside. Inside, wow, Terry's visuals were 
really pretty. Pretty decorations. That was a very nice setup. I loved the bank 
of 27+ computer monitors in front of the DJs, with flowers set on top of them 
and between them.

nice people, though. I was tired and stayed in one place most of the time, but 
I enjoyed the music and the atmosphere. I enjoyed the set by Marc(o) and Bam 
a lot. 

Who else went?

Sitting here at work this morning, still groggy from
Saturday nights events I just can't stop smiling.

I want to thank each and everyone of the people who
attended. Without you there would have been no party,
and there would have been no great vibe. Thanks to the
people who hung out with me and made me smile and
laugh all night. You guys made my party.

Thanks to Scott Hampton for going to that punk party
down the street and promoting with me. :D And thanks
to Tina, after we found out it was the wrong party,
driving us to the club down the street hehe. You guys
definitely made it fun!

Thanks to SE/30 for zooming me back to the bart
station Sunday morning! LOL Crazy Mofo!!!!

Thank you Dragn'fly and Terri for remiscing with me
about the old days in Sac. LOL So good to see you guys
there. You have been there through my whole raving
"career", and I love you guys<3

And last but not least, thanks to all the old heads
who made it out. Seeing you again is like being
reunited with family, and I love you all.

This party has made me feel alive inside again. I
haven't felt this way in a long time. It was magical.
I'm so happy I feel satisfied with the scene again.
Its so addicting and great. I'm still totally high off
of it. Yay for raving! I love you guys!

FUCKING PLUR!!!!!

-Delia<3

damnit.

the Autobots (Broke/UK)

The Autobots, who were conceived during a crazy acid flashback moment
in the year 2323, are set to travel back in time to California 2006,
ready to embrace their star spangled cousins, in their only west coast
dates this year.
Still buzzing from winning the "Breakthru Label" award at the
prestigious Breakspoll awards in London, they have been working
relentlessly to maintain the quality sounds that have become
synonymous with their successful "BROKE" imprint!

check the heaviest breaks, beats and basslines that you'll hear
anywhere on the planet this year!

Subject: [sfraves] bsp: Sat.Aug.19 [KONTROL] presents Brian Aneurysm (Spectral.PokerFlat:London)

Saturday, August 19

[ K O N T R O L ]

minimal techno + avant house
every 3rd Saturday at Rx Gallery


featuring from London in his SF debut:


BRIAN ANEURYSM   (aka EchoPilot)

iron box . spectral . poker flat . traum . sub-static
morris audio . immigrant . triebstoff . tic tac toe

Raised in Vienna and schooled in the ways of quality techno in Dallas
in the late 90's, Bernhard Pucher has been DJing and producing for
some of the world's most respected labels (including his own Iron Box
Music) for nearly a decade. These days he lives in London and, when
not performing throughout the world, creates electro/industrial-tinged
tracks as Confutatis, moody minimal techno as EchoPilot, and
deliciously sinister dancefloor tech-house as Brian Aneurysm. Catch
his unique style in this SF debut performance.  www.briananeurysm.com


plus special guest just added!


JASON SHORT  (aka DJ Sattva)

funkycozy . COTK . auralism records

Recent Miami transplant Jason Short (formerly known as DJ Sattva)
caught our attention last year when we heard some of his outstanding
DJ mixes.  His heady, deep, and dirty blend of minimal and tech-house
has landed him recent slots opening for Matthew Dear and DJ Traxx, as
well as a permanent spot on the always-solid FunkyCozy roster, the
collective that's brought SF the likes of Damian Lazarus, Pier Bucci,
Matt Tolfrey and many more.  www.funkycozy.com


with [KONTROL] residents:

ALLAND BYALLO  ( liebe*detail . kvadrat produkt . mo's ferry )
SAMMY D  ( classic . dirtybird . utensil )
CRAIG KUNA   ( concept sf . esdjco )


Rx Gallery art exhibition:  Uplifting Vengeance 2006 World Tour

The art this month is INTENSE!  Worth the price of admission alone.

Check out a sneak peek here:
http://www.rxgallery.com/images/artistworks/skinner.jpg

________________________________________________

Rx Gallery
132 Eddy @ Mason, SF / 415.474.7973
9pm-2am / 21+ / $10
________________________________________________


Check our website for full bios, pics and lots FREE music!
http://www.kontrolsf.com

[KONTROL] on MySpace:
http://www.myspace.com/kontrolsf

View the flyer here:
http://www.kontrolsf.com/K15F.jpg
http://www.kontrolsf.com/K15B.jpg

________________________________________________


==== BIOGRAPHY ====

Bernhard Pucher has been producing electronic music for almost a
decade. He started buying records in '96 and ended up getting into
production within the same year. Inspired by the local dance
community, he started working on his craft in his home town of Vienna,
Austria.

In 1998, he moved to Dallas, Texas where he experienced a completely
new environment for electronic music. He met a lot of people who were
not just into dance, but also into more experimental forms of
electronica, including down tempo, industrial, breaks, and hard
techno. This new environment shaped his style, and with the help of
his friend Stefan Anion, he started getting into playing live as well.

But by 2000, a drastic shift happened. He started teaming up with
mutual techno lover Eric Estornel (aka Maetrik, Mariel Ito) who then
introduced him to a form of music he had not properly experienced
until then: Minimal and Electro. That influenced his musical style so
much that by 2001 he started his own label IRON BOX MUSIC. With his
background in industrial and heavy metal, his minimal sound started to
take shape in its own way.

In 2005, his journey brought him to London, by then with many
releases, remixes and appearances under his belt on labels like Ai
Records, Sub-Static, Spectral, Traum, Morris Audio, Ware, Onitor,
Poker Flat, Tangent Beats, and of course his own label, Iron Box
Music.


==== LINKS ====

Website:
http://www.briananeurysm.com

Complete Discography @ Discogs:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Brian+Aneurysm

Interview:
http://www.inthemix.com.au/features/16642/


==== AUDIO ====

EchoPilot - Emptiness (...a KONTROL favorite!)
http://www.kontrolsf.com/AUD/EchoPilot_-_Emptiness.mp3

Brian Aneurysm - Iron Box Sessions #13 (DJ set)
http://www.ironboxmusic.com/audio/brian_aneurysm_IBS13.mp3


==== REVIEWS ====

Brian Aneurysm - Succubus - Sub-Static

Sub Static return with humorously named Brian Aneurysm who drops 4
tracks of straight up techno hijinks for the heads. Brian hails from
Texas - past releases have been on his own, so hot it hurts, Iron Box
techouse label, as well as Poker Flat and Ware. After his venomously
brilliant double ep "Amplified" (sub static #28), the Texan has now
upgraded his sharp-edged techno funk wrecks to an ugly assed nasty
jacker on the title cut, which doesn't even have to be played
backwards to spread its seductive poison. Diabolic stuff, and great
material for the more darkside inclined clubsound. Damaging.

Echopilot - Fragile EP - Morris Audio CitySport Edition

Produced by Brian Pucher (aka Brian Aneurysm) under his Echopilot
guise, this is akin to taking one part minimal Richie Hawtin and one
part quirky Derrick Carter and one part silky Timewriter; and blending
them together into a deep, minimal concoction.  Simple rhythms,
eclectic (and sometimes disturbing) vocal samples, jazzy stabs and a
ton of atmosphere come together to take you on a journey through the
mind of a mad scientist. This is about as funky and tricked out as
anything you are likely to hear, and one of the best productions of
the year to this point. Exquisite Stuff.

Brian Aneurysm - The End of Logic - Iron Box Music

Bernard Pucher comes back under his alias Brian Aneurysm, opening the
year harder than ever before with a minimal techno stomper. He is
known for his dark and twisted minimal, but on this record, he
combines that with his love for good old techno, and creates an
energy-laden EP called THE END OF LOGIC. The original is distorted,
thick and crunchy with a twisted vocal ...you know, the kind we've
come to love from Brian Aneurysm. The B-Side offers 2dollarEgg-style
thump tracks that combine great production with minimal flavour
resulting in dancefloor mania.

Whatever you do, hit up the Green Dolphin Room on a Monday night for the
longest-running deep house night in the city. Diz rocked it when I was there
last week.

Also, The Note has good music on Thursdays, and Smartbar has Tintonton on
thursday & Jon Tejada this Friday.

Good luck, and have lots of fun. I totally dig Chicago.

~juju

Damn I just got back from Chicago last night!

It was great. Chicago is an amazing city. I haven't been there since 99 and 
boy did my memory not serve me well. I am thoroughly impressed.  Played a 
small club on thursday (which reminded me of many smaller SF clubs) called 
Vertigo.  The whole bar was painted in themes of Hitchcock movies (Birds, 
Vertigo, North by Northwest, hitchcock himself) it was awesome.

Then I played in the Penthouse of "Vision" on Saturday.  That club was 
amazing.  5 stories packed full of people.  Armin Van Horn who I'd never 
heard of was playing in the main room and he deffinatly rocked it.  I would 
say if you are going to be in Chicago don't miss this place.  Also from what 
some of my friends in Chicago say don't miss "Sound Bar".  Its a bit more 
upscale, but super dope.  We walked by it but didn't go it.

Chicago has a huge day party coming up that goes from Noon to Midnight with 
the likes of Tiesto, Deep Dish, Dave Clarke, Bad Boy Bill,  Benny Benassi, 
Junkie XL and more.  The event is called PURENATION and is on September 2nd.

Sander Kleinenberg is playing Vision on August 19th, Theres a campout called 
"Outlawed and Ecstatic present Campout" that looks pretty good thats on 
September 2-3.

And dont' forget Earthdance is on September 15,16, & 17th.

A few sites to check out would be www.midwest-edm.com also 
www.midwest-underground.com there's some good info on those forums.

:)

Paul \

Forgive the long post.  I thought this article was worth sharing, but =20=

you must be a subscriber to view all of it.

Apollo




Jaron's World: The Murder of Mystery

How Silicon Valley joined the superstitious fringe as the enemy of =20
open inquiry.

By Jaron Lanier

DISCOVER Vol. 27 No. 09 | September 2006

Last week I had a jarring conversation with one of the most =20
influential figures in Silicon Valley. Me: I wish more kids were =20
learning to be musicians. He: In 10 years computers will be able to =20
use a combination of artificial intelligence and massed data from the =20=

Internet to generate music better than human musicians. We can =20
already use these techniques to choose hit songs more accurately than =20=

record executives. Musicianship will be an obsolete profession by the =20=

time today's kids grow up. There might be good reasons to teach kids =20
music, but creating a new generation of professional musicians is not =20=

one of them.

This was one of those moments when I wondered at what's become of =20
computer culture. The remark was the kind of thing Marvin Minsky, the =20=

legendary MIT professor and one of the fathers of artificial =20
intelligence, used to say to me when I was a young researcher to piss =20=

me off and make me think. But there were unmistakable layers of humor =20=

and irony in Marvin's provocations. Many of today's Silicon Valley =20
thought leaders seem to have embraced what used to be speculations as =20=

certainties, without the spirit of unbounded curiosity that =20
originally gave rise to them.

Ideas that used to be tucked away in the obscure world of artificial =20
intelligence labs have gone mainstream in tech culture. The basic =20
tenet of this new culture is that all of reality, including humans, =20
is one big information system. The meaning of life, in this view, is =20
making that system function at ever-higher "levels of description." =20
People pretend to know what "levels of description" means, though I =20
doubt anyone really does. A Web page is thought to represent a higher =20=

level of description than a single letter, while a brain is a higher =20
level than a Web page. An increasingly common extension of this =20
notion is that the Net as a whole is or soon will be a higher level =20
than a brain.

There's nothing special about the place of humans in this scheme. =20
Soon computers will get so big and fast and the Net so rich with =20
information that we will be obsolete, either left behind or subsumed =20
into some cyber-superhuman something.

Silicon Valley culture has recently taken to enshrining this abstract =20=

idea and spreading it in a novel way. Since implementation speaks =20
louder than words, ideas can be spread in the designs of software. If =20=

you believe the distinction between the roles of people and computers =20=

is starting to dissolve, you might express that, as some friends of =20
mine at Microsoft once did, by designing features for a word =20
processor that are supposed to know what you want, such as when you =20
want to start an outline. You might have had the experience of having =20=

Word suddenly determine that you are creating an indented outline at =20
the wrong moment. While I am all for the automation of petty tasks, =20
this is different. =46rom my point of view this type of design feature =20=

is nonsense, since you end up having to learn more than you would =20
otherwise in order to manipulate such software's expectations of you. =20=

The real function of the feature isn't to make life easier=97it is to =20=

express a new philosophy.

For decades I've been complaining about antihuman computer culture, =20
and I frequently end up attracting some unwelcome allies. I seek to =20
influence young technical people=97and I think I have been able to do =20=

that=97but I also seem to excite some other folks who get it all wrong. =20=

I'm not the slightest bit Luddite. I don't believe that something =20
natural is necessarily any more meaningful or true than something =20
artificial. I'm actually a raving technological utopian!

A description of my particular utopian thinking will have to wait for =20=

another month's column, but I believe the most beautiful =20
possibilities come from treating people as mysterious wells of =20
meaning and using technology to find new ways to connect people to =20
each other. The important point is that while I'm willing to go very =20
far in imagining what information technology might be like in the =20
future, I don't assume that I know quite what a person is, and =20
therefore I don't attempt to reduce personhood in my designs.

These days I feel as though I'm walking on a tightrope, with a crowd =20
of ravenous faux robotic nerds on one side and a gaggle of =20
sentimental antiquarians on the other. I try not to fall to either side.

In a sense, this is a continuation of old battles sparked by the =20
Enlightenment. You can imagine some of the traditional religious =20
enemies of the Enlightenment on one side of the rope. The least =20
likable have always been those driven by the power that comes from =20
perpetuating church empires built on the fear of death. This was and =20
remains the setup for popes and bishops who would bother to persecute =20=

a Galileo or ridicule a Darwin.

Of course, there are also many religious or spiritual people who =20
understandably wonder about questions related to death and who worry =20
whether meaning, beauty, and other deeply human qualities can survive =20=

the cold scrutiny of rational inquiry. If a new technologically =20
informed worldview isn't attractive to such people, I think =20
technologists ought to change their culture to make it more =20
welcoming, and that is particularly true for product designers.

There are also lunatics congregating on the other side of the =20
tightrope: those who are treating the mere appearance of rationality =20
as a fetish. Communists loved to overrule science, for instance, even =20=

though they cloaked themselves in language and even clothing styles =20
that were supposed to evoke rationality. In the Soviet Union, the =20
ideas of Trofim Lysenko, an anti-Darwinian pseudoscientist, were =20
preferred over reality, contributing to disastrous agricultural =20
policies. Similar things are happening today when business interests =20
suppress global-warming research.

You can always tell when an idea comes from fake rationalists. The =20
telltale sign is a premature decline in mystery, specifically the =20
kind of mystery that can be tackled through testable hypotheses. =20
Intelligent design falls into this category. If you believe a =20
biological structure is nothing more than a fashion decision made by =20
God (or an alien), there's nothing you can do to explain it beyond =20
that; you're done. While it might at first seem to enshrine mystery, =20
intelligent design actually insulates us from the endless, intriguing =20=

mysteries of nature by providing one answer in advance for everything.

It would have been possible to treat Darwin's insights in exactly the =20=

same way. A lazy, nonscientific Darwinian could say "Everything =20
evolved" and be done with it. Some of my misguided colleagues do just =20=

that when they say things like, "Computers will inevitably evolve to =20
correct flaws in our posthuman visions, such as the fact that =20
software is endlessly buggy and needs to be fixed by human programmers."

The reason Darwin's ideas are so powerful is that there was another =20
option. His ideas opened a type of path not opened by intelligent =20
design: methodically challenging the initial base of ideas and =20
refining it until it becomes something far more specific and useful. =20
Biology benefited from an intellectual revolution provided by Darwin =20
but has in many ways left him behind. Biologists now deal in genes, =20
viruses, and a world of other objects and ideas Darwin didn't know =20
about.

Lately the problem of premature mystery reduction has cropped up more =20=

than once within technical cultures. The tone taken by some string =20
theorists reminds me of what I'm criticizing in recent Silicon Valley =20=

thinking (see "Tangled Up in Strings" on page 68).

Is reality a giant information system and people just arbitrarily =20
defined portions of it? Wrong question! Information theory is =20
tremendously useful, but it doesn't tell us anything until it's been =20
used. The idea that you might someday understand something is =20
different from actually understanding it, or even knowing the right =20
questions to ask. The big idea behind the new fake rationality is so =20
diffuse that it's useless, except as a cultural badge.

That brings me back to my misguided colleague and his ideas about the =20=

future of music. There are a multitude of mysteries prematurely =20
reduced by his point of view. We don't know what music is, exactly. =20
We don't know much about how the brain works. We don't even have good =20=

experimental methods to tell when we're bending over backward to make =20=

a computer merely seem smart.

If I really believed that science was reducing the mystery of life, I =20=

would feel claustrophobic, but just the opposite is true. The more =20
science I learn, the more mysteries I learn about, and the richer =20
life becomes. I wonder if a technical culture that was better at =20
avoiding premature claims of mystery reduction would find more =20
friends among the sensitive, "spiritual" people I referred to =20
earlier. Some extreme religious people will probably never embrace =20
science, but I often wonder if the harshness of the way some =20
scientists talk about the nerd future is driving reasonable people away.

Avoiding a premature decline in mystery is also a great principle for =20=

making better software. You don't have to pretend to know what music =20
is to give musicians new ways to work together, but you do have to =20
believe that human musicians are important. The genuinely radical =20
ideas in computer science come when people work honestly within the =20
boundaries of what we don't know.

  https://www.discover.com/issues/sep-06/departments/murderofmystery/?=20=

page=3D2




apollo@speakeasy.org

MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo

Tribenet:   http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k

Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm



"No sage or savior has ever endorsed greed and gluttony as a path =20
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and =20
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, =20
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and =20
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can =20
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and =20
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond =20
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative =20
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in =20
squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of =20
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will =20
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"



--Apple-Mail-1--874969663--

    Cajun food? In San Francisco? Don't kid yourselves. The only real 
Cajun food is served in little dirty ass shacks in rural Louisiana by 
dirty ass Cajun people that say things like "sha." So, unless your food 
is covered in spices and has been cooked by someone who thinks 60,000 
people in a swamp constitutes a big city and contains crawfish in some 
way, it's not real Cajun food. It's a bastardized Californian version of it.

    Sorry for the rant, but being from Louisiana I've eaten a lot of 
Cajun food, and I can say with a fairly high degree of certainty that 
you can't find the real stuff out here.

    Fools.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] The rave scene and what it's all about?

    Even if the food is cooked exactly the same way it's still not the 
same. The ambiance is different, you don't get the same culture. 
Further, the air and water are different here, which has a big impact on 
the way food is going to taste. You may have had *some* crawfish out 
here, but it probably wasn't included in almost every dish. And even if 
you've had crawfish here, it's not the same as crawfish that was pulled 
out of the swamp the same day you're eating it.

    I also seriously doubt you've ever had boudain here, which is 
another Cajun staple.

    Lookit, I lived in Louisiana for seventeen years, I know all about 
some Cajun food and culture. The food is just not the same without the 
culture. You can't get the culture with your food out here. Not that you 
can even get properly cooked Cajun food here.

I had such a great time at Obsoleet! The whole night felt like a lesson in
SF Rave history, and indeed I was schooled. Sorry I missed your set, Marco =
=96
now I owe *you* dinner. Thanks to Bam for introducing me to so many people,
Justin Hale for talking me into my little indiscretion, and Osby for taking
the money shot. AndyW tastes like techno.

The lineup was dope =96 not very often I get to hear so many genres at one
party (oh and the sound was good too) and I danced all night. Huuuuge love
to the Fingermonsters =96 together you form a super house robot. We must ma=
ke
you voltron-like interlocking costumes. And yes, Heaven Scent was the
perfect end to the dance party.

Double yeys for all the hardore people who made it out to dance in the park
on Sunday. Pomegranate mimosas are grate. Or something like that.
Props.

~juju

remember for

Happy Birthday Bam and Karlo!!

This event is going to take place in the Bunny Meadow in Golden Gate
Park. This is
located on the Fulton side of the park near 6th and 7th streets. Right
behind the
Conservatory of Flowers. Music will start at noon and go untill
sundown... See you
all there...

                       A S P I R E

other!

Subject: [sfraves] bsp: [KONTROL] with Brian Aneurysm + Jason Short ...SATURDAY!

Saturday, August 19

[ K O N T R O L ]

minimal techno + avant house
every 3rd Saturday at Rx Gallery


featuring from London in his SF debut:


BRIAN ANEURYSM   (aka EchoPilot)

iron box . spectral . poker flat . traum . sub-static
morris audio . immigrant . triebstoff . tic tac toe

Raised in Vienna and schooled in the ways of quality techno in Dallas
in the late 90's, Bernhard Pucher has been DJing and producing for
some of the world's most respected labels (including his own Iron Box
Music) for nearly a decade. These days he lives in London and, when
not performing throughout the world, creates electro/industrial-tinged
tracks as Confutatis, moody minimal techno as EchoPilot, and
deliciously sinister dancefloor tech-house as Brian Aneurysm. Catch
his unique style in this SF debut performance.  www.briananeurysm.com


plus special guest just added!


JASON SHORT  (aka Sattva)

funkycozy . coalition of the killing . auralism records

Recent Miami transplant Jason Short (formerly known as Sattva) caught
our attention last year when we heard some of his outstanding DJ
mixes.  His heady, deep, and dirty blend of minimal and tech-house has
landed him recent slots opening for Damian Lazarus and DJ Traxx, as
well as a permanent spot on the always-solid FunkyCozy roster, the
collective that's brought SF the likes of Pier Bucci, Matt Tolfrey,
Damian Lazarus and many more.  www.funkycozy.com


with [KONTROL] residents:

ALLAND BYALLO  ( liebe*detail . kvadrat produkt . mo's ferry )
SAMMY D  ( classic . dirtybird . utensil )
CRAIG KUNA   ( concept sf . esdjco )


Rx Gallery art exhibition:  Uplifting Vengeance 2006 World Tour

The art this month is INTENSE!  Worth the price of admission alone.

Check out a sneak peek here:
http://www.rxgallery.com/images/artistworks/skinner.jpg

==== BIOGRAPHIES ====


BRIAN ANEURYSM

Bernhard Pucher has been producing electronic music for almost a
decade.  He started buying records in '96 and ended up getting into
production within the same year.  Inspired by the local dance
community, he started working on his craft in his home town of Vienna,
Austria.  In 1998, he moved to Dallas, Texas where he experienced a
completely new environment for electronic music.  He met a lot of
people who were not just into dance, but also into more experimental
forms of electronica, including down tempo, industrial, breaks, and
hard techno.  This new environment shaped his style, and with the help
of his friend Stefan Anion, he started getting into playing live as
well.  But by 2000, a drastic shift happened. He started teaming up
with mutual techno lover Eric Estornel (aka Maetrik, Mariel Ito) who
then introduced him to a form of music he had not properly experienced
until then: Minimal and Electro. That influenced his musical style so
much that by 2001 he started his own label IRON BOX MUSIC. With his
background in industrial and heavy metal, his minimal sound started to
take shape in its own way.  In 2005, his journey brought him to
London, by then with many releases, remixes and appearances under his
belt on labels like Ai Records, Sub-Static, Spectral, Traum, Morris
Audio, Ware, Onitor, Poker Flat, Tangent Beats, and of course his own
label, Iron Box Music.


JASON SHORT

Jason Short began spinning and producing underground dance music in
1997 in San Francisco.  He soon after relocated to Florida, where he
earned a degree in Recording Engineering and began producing with some
friends as Biogenesis.  His productions caught the attention of
Xplosion and Nepol Records, and eight releases and several remixes
followed. After obtaining his degree, Jason wanted to return to the
roots of house music and moved to Chicago in 2001.  Inspired and
focused, he flourished in the studio and soon found himself djing all
over Chicago.  In 2002, Jason met Hac Le while fighting over the same
vinyl at world famous Gramaphone Records. The two immediately formed a
synergistic musical bond and began dropping mean 2x6x2 (2 mixers 6
turntables 2 djs) tag-team sets which quickly gained them critical
acclaim and a monthly residency in Mexico City with Global Trip.  In
2003, Jason headed to Miami to reconnect with Marc Smith of Biognesis
and work on their next project, Coaltion of the Killing, and develop
their new label, Auralism Records.  He has spent the past two years
honing his skills as a musician, dj, producer, and engineer, traveling
regularly to play with the FunkyCozy crew in San Francisco.  His
vibrations from the decks range from twisted, bass-heavy, floor-moving
techno to flowing, melodic, glitchy downtempo and experimental.  The
sounds are psychedelic and deep, glistening with serotonin-inducing
shimmers and infectious rhythms that push your body into motion.


==== LINKS ====

http://www.briananeurysm.com

Complete Discography @ Discogs:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Brian+Aneurysm

Interview:
http://www.inthemix.com.au/features/16642/


==== AUDIO ====

EchoPilot - Emptiness (sample)   (...a KONTROL favorite!)
http://www.kontrolsf.com/AUD/EchoPilot_-_Emptiness.mp3

Brian Aneurysm - Iron Box Sessions #13 (DJ set)
http://www.ironboxmusic.com/audio/brian_aneurysm_IBS13.mp3


==== REVIEWS ====

Brian Aneurysm - Succubus - Sub-Static

Sub Static return with humorously named Brian Aneurysm who drops 4
tracks of straight up techno hijinks for the heads. Brian hails from
Texas - past releases have been on his own, so hot it hurts, Iron Box
techouse label, as well as Poker Flat and Ware. After his venomously
brilliant double ep "Amplified" (sub static #28), the Texan has now
upgraded his sharp-edged techno funk wrecks to an ugly assed nasty
jacker on the title cut, which doesn't even have to be played
backwards to spread its seductive poison. Diabolic stuff, and great
material for the more darkside inclined clubsound. Damaging.

Echopilot - Fragile EP - Morris Audio CitySport Edition

Produced by Brian Pucher (aka Brian Aneurysm) under his Echopilot
guise, this is akin to taking one part minimal Richie Hawtin and one
part quirky Derrick Carter and one part silky Timewriter; and blending
them together into a deep, minimal concoction.  Simple rhythms,
eclectic (and sometimes disturbing) vocal samples, jazzy stabs and a
ton of atmosphere come together to take you on a journey through the
mind of a mad scientist. This is about as funky and tricked out as
anything you are likely to hear, and one of the best productions of
the year to this point. Exquisite Stuff.

Brian Aneurysm - The End of Logic - Iron Box Music

Bernard Pucher comes back under his alias Brian Aneurysm, opening the
year harder than ever before with a minimal techno stomper. He is
known for his dark and twisted minimal, but on this record, he
combines that with his love for good old techno, and creates an
energy-laden EP called THE END OF LOGIC. The original is distorted,
thick and crunchy with a twisted vocal ...you know, the kind we've
come to love from Brian Aneurysm. The B-Side offers 2dollarEgg-style
thump tracks that combine great production with minimal flavour
resulting in dancefloor mania.

Subject: [sfraves] OH yeah... late WR's: Full Melt, Telic Day Party,
      & OW @ Oasis Monthly

So a few weeks back, when i la la la la la la la about Full Melt.. well.
.it was a Dope night.. i have to admit.. it was Reallyl Dope... & yes.. I
did bartend for 1/2 that night ;)  I mean... i kinda got mondo yucky 1.2
way through the night, & kinda got put outta commision.. literally :(

But before that.. it was Dope... I mean... like i got there early for set
up.. set up my bar... what was mondo way Groovy Bad Ass was well.. me &
Ripple went to go pick up the headliners, Pinch & Distance, @ the radio
station... then after that.. we went out to eat @ McD's (the line @ In N
OUt was way long) & for like an hour.. we just like talked & ate & like
Pinch & Distance.. really Awesome "English Mates" :)

Now the trippy part about the party was... the main room was aaaaaall
Grime & Dubstep... I mean.. 1 DJ threw down some 2 Step in the middle of
his set.... I think that was SubTek... but it was just trippy... & every1
who was there was totally feelin' it:)  The 2nd room had breaks & that was
fun :)  It was a Dope party & like aalmost eeeveryone from every scene was
there almost :)

Oh yeah.. there's pictures of me & my sisters in the album 'cause there
wre here that weekend for my Cousin's 18th Bday Shindig i ditched out on
to go to Full Melt...


http://s54.photobucket.com/albums/g100/MadWicked/Full%20Melt%207-29-2006/

The next weekend... I went to the Telic Day Party... it was fun... like it
was @ Lake Elizabeth in Freemont.. OK.. so that park.. Hello 2day.. got
HUUUUGE!!  LIke last time i was there was for ASR's last Day party ummm..
2 1/2 years ago... so yeah... it got bigger!

The music throughout when i was there was Happy HArdcore. house, breaks,
trance, 80's, some old school hop hop, & Jungle!  It was Dope!  It was
also Groovy seein' my Candy Fam again!  YAAAAAY

Oh yeah.. there was also like mondo BBQ action goin' on :)  Made some beef
that i stole ffrom my Mom's tupperware in the fridge.. lol :X  Si that
Dope!!!

Statyed there 'til about like 8 something & like Ms DJ D gave me a ride to
Oakland where i went to the OtherWorld Shindig for the Label Record
Release, "Oaklyn" I think the label's called... WOW.. such a fun night...
OK.. 1st off.. this Dude i met like a year & 1/2 ago, Uriah, who i talk to
on AIM & On the phone all the time, was there... lol.. i met him like
before he enrolled @ that school in Emeryville...

But yeah... oh my gosh.. so the music was Sick... there 1 Dude.. strait up
played old skool hop hop, 80's electro yummy, & man... i danced hard that
night!  Oh yeah.. they also had like all these comedians perform.. i
thouhgt only 2 of them were Hella funny... but they were all good!  Then
there was this live singer Chic who sang & rapped!  It was Dope!!!  Really
Dope night!

http://s96.photobucket.com/albums/l188/YummyBeats/Telic%20OtherWorld%208-5-2006/

but in all honesty.. i'm still kinda high off last weekend & Obsoleet...
man... loloololmao.. Hello 2day... best fuckin' night in a long time!!! 
YAAAY!!  :)  But ya know.. i never feel complete until i posted up where i
been groovin' lately:)  Love Ya Ravers!


-- 
Take Care <3
Peace=->Jus' Me =-> O§bY {8O)

Subject: RE: [sfraves] OH yeah... late WR's: Full Melt, Telic Day Party, & OW @ Oasis

Full Melt.. probably one of the sickest parties I have been to in a long 
time.. could not tear myself away from the main room for more than 5 
minutes.  Ripple's set was one of the most amazing sets I have ever heard, 
period.  The K probably helped.. but ya.. it was wicked fucking good shit!

My favorite part of the night was around 5am.. the walls were all blacked 
out, no light, co2 pumping into the room, lasers going off in every 
direction, music dripping from the ceiling in tangible sticky ways.. and 
then there was this one woman, cute as hell, in braids and a little school 
girl dress.. prancing around like she was on a horse.  I like to call her 
PonyGirl.  At one point she was galloping in place in front of me, looking 
back to make sure I noticed, and then galloped off.. omg.. I just wanted to 
ride her so bad..lol!

Ya.. I was fully melted after that night.. drivin home at 6am :)

Episode 15!  Can you believe it?

We're looking forward to another killer show!

Expect some deep, dark, heavy, pretty and intense minimal techno and
tech-house blended together in a very unique way.  Fans of our Troy Pierce
show in January will definitely dig!  If you're not afraid of a little
darkness in your funk, you're in for quite a treat. Make sure to check out
the ridiculously awesome EchoPilot track (in the audio section below) to get
a taste of what you're in for.

Also of note is that the art this month is really worth seeing!  Great
stuff.

Hope to see some of you there.

____________________________________


Saturday, August 19

[ K O N T R O L ]

minimal techno + avant house
every 3rd Saturday at Rx Gallery


featuring from London in his SF debut:


BRIAN ANEURYSM   (aka EchoPilot)

iron box . spectral . poker flat . traum . sub-static
morris audio . immigrant . triebstoff . tic tac toe

Raised in Vienna and schooled in the ways of quality techno in Dallas in the
late 90's, Bernhard Pucher has been DJing and producing for some of the
world's most respected labels (including his own Iron Box Music) for nearly
a decade. These days he lives in London and, when not performing throughout
the world, creates electro/industrial-tinged tracks as Confutatis, moody
minimal techno as EchoPilot, and deliciously sinister dancefloor tech-house
as Brian Aneurysm. Catch his unique style in this SF debut performance.
www.briananeurysm.com


plus special guest just added!


JASON SHORT  (aka Sattva)

funkycozy . coalition of the killing . auralism records

Recent Miami transplant Jason Short (formerly known as Sattva) caught our
attention last year when we heard some of his outstanding DJ mixes.  His
heady, deep, and dirty blend of minimal and tech-house has landed him recent
slots opening for Damian Lazarus and DJ Traxx, as well as a permanent spot
on the always-solid FunkyCozy roster, the collective that's brought SF the
likes of Pier Bucci, Matt Tolfrey, Damian Lazarus and many more.
www.funkycozy.com


with [KONTROL] residents:

ALLAND BYALLO  ( liebe*detail . kvadrat produkt . mo's ferry )
SAMMY D  ( classic . dirtybird . utensil )
CRAIG KUNA   ( concept sf . esdjco )


Rx Gallery art exhibition:  Uplifting Vengeance 2006 World Tour

The art this month is INTENSE!  Don't miss it.

Check out a sneak peek here:
http://www.rxgallery.com/images/artistworks/skinner.jpg

132 Eddy @ Mason, SF / 415.474.7973
9pm-2am / 21+ / $10

==== BIOGRAPHIES ====


BRIAN ANEURYSM

Bernhard Pucher has been producing electronic music for almost a decade.  He
started buying records in '96 and ended up getting into production within
the same year.  Inspired by the local dance community, he started working on
his craft in his home town of Vienna, Austria.  In 1998, he moved to Dallas,
Texas where he experienced a completely new environment for electronic
music.  He met a lot of people who were not just into dance, but also into
more experimental forms of electronica, including down tempo, industrial,
breaks, and hard techno.  This new environment shaped his style, and with
the help of his friend Stefan Anion, he started getting into playing live as
well.  But by 2000, a drastic shift happened. He started teaming up with
mutual techno lover Eric Estornel (aka Maetrik, Mariel Ito) who then
introduced him to a form of music he had not properly experienced until
then: Minimal and Electro. That influenced his musical style so much that by
2001 he started his own label IRON BOX MUSIC. With his background in
industrial and heavy metal, his minimal sound started to take shape in its
own way.  In 2005, his journey brought him to London, by then with many
releases, remixes and appearances under his belt on labels like Ai Records,
Sub-Static, Spectral, Traum, Morris Audio, Ware, Onitor, Poker Flat, Tangent
Beats, and of course his own label, Iron Box Music.


JASON SHORT

Jason Short began spinning and producing underground dance music in 1997 in
San Francisco.  He soon after relocated to Florida, where he earned a degree
in Recording Engineering and began producing with some friends as
Biogenesis.  His productions caught the attention of Xplosion and Nepol
Records, and eight releases and several remixes followed. After obtaining
his degree, Jason wanted to return to the roots of house music and moved to
Chicago in 2001.  Inspired and focused, he flourished in the studio and soon
found himself djing all over Chicago.  In 2002, Jason met Hac Le while
fighting over the same vinyl at world famous Gramaphone Records. The two
immediately formed a synergistic musical bond and began dropping mean 2x6x2
(2 mixers 6 turntables 2 djs) tag-team sets which quickly gained them
critical acclaim and a monthly residency in Mexico City with Global Trip.
In 2003, Jason headed to Miami to reconnect with Marc Smith of Biognesis and
work on their next project, Coaltion of the Killing, and develop their new
label, Auralism Records.  He has spent the past two years honing his skills
as a musician, dj, producer, and engineer, traveling regularly to play with
the FunkyCozy crew in San Francisco.  His vibrations from the decks range
from twisted, bass-heavy, floor-moving techno to flowing, melodic, glitchy
downtempo and experimental.  The sounds are psychedelic and deep, glistening
with serotonin-inducing shimmers and infectious rhythms that push your body
into motion.


==== LINKS ====

http://www.briananeurysm.com

Complete Discography @ Discogs:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Brian+Aneurysm

Interview:
http://www.inthemix.com.au/features/16642/


==== AUDIO ====

EchoPilot - Emptiness (sample)   (...a KONTROL favorite!)
http://www.kontrolsf.com/AUD/EchoPilot_-_Emptiness.mp3

Brian Aneurysm - Iron Box Sessions #13 (DJ set)
http://www.ironboxmusic.com/audio/brian_aneurysm_IBS13.mp3


==== REVIEWS ====

Brian Aneurysm - Succubus - Sub-Static

Sub Static return with humorously named Brian Aneurysm who drops 4 tracks of
straight up techno hijinks for the heads. Brian hails from Texas - past
releases have been on his own, so hot it hurts, Iron Box techouse label, as
well as Poker Flat and Ware. After his venomously brilliant double ep
"Amplified" (sub static #28), the Texan has now upgraded his sharp-edged
techno funk wrecks to an ugly assed nasty jacker on the title cut, which
doesn't even have to be played backwards to spread its seductive poison.
Diabolic stuff, and great material for the more darkside inclined clubsound.
Damaging.

Echopilot - Fragile EP - Morris Audio CitySport Edition

Produced by Brian Pucher (aka Brian Aneurysm) under his Echopilot guise,
this is akin to taking one part minimal Richie Hawtin and one part quirky
Derrick Carter and one part silky Timewriter; and blending them together
into a deep, minimal concoction.  Simple rhythms, eclectic (and sometimes
disturbing) vocal samples, jazzy stabs and a ton of atmosphere come together
to take you on a journey through the mind of a mad scientist. This is about
as funky and tricked out as anything you are likely to hear, and one of the
best productions of the year to this point. Exquisite Stuff.

Brian Aneurysm - The End of Logic - Iron Box Music

Bernard Pucher comes back under his alias Brian Aneurysm, opening the year
harder than ever before with a minimal techno stomper. He is known for his
dark and twisted minimal, but on this record, he combines that with his love
for good old techno, and creates an energy-laden EP called THE END OF LOGIC.
The original is distorted, thick and crunchy with a twisted vocal ...you
know, the kind we've come to love from Brian Aneurysm. The B-Side offers
2dollarEgg-style thump tracks that combine great production with minimal
flavour resulting in dancefloor mania.

------=_Part_18055_15934280.1155999887879
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1; format=flowed

Before burning man each year, several of us collect folks' 10 and 20 pound
racing nitrous tanks and fill them with pure environmentally friendly sulfur
free NO2 for off street racing purposes out at the black rock desert, or any
off street track. (vehicles on public roads are not permitted to have NO2
tanks installed to boost performance)

NO2 powered art cars with dedicated 10 and 20 pound tanks deliver much
greater performance gains than vehicles utilizing the tiny cream charger
storage devices which cost 5-10 times more.

If you are a "racing" fan and understand what we are providing for racers in
the bay area, please drop an email off list.

ben

The details: Saturday, Aug 19th, zombies will be storming the corner of
Market and Sansome at 2:30p. We will then walk/limp/crawl to Powell Station
by 3:00p. There will be a big massacre on Powell between Market and
O'Farrel. We'll Pick up stragglers at Union Square by 3:30p. See the <
http://eatbrains.com/mob2006/images/mobmap.jpg>Map

How to participate: Plant yourself somewhere along our route. Show up in
plain clothes minus anything of value. Wear a small piece of duct tape (or
similar) clearly visible on your torso. Attract our attention somehow.
(screaming "aaaiiieeee! zombies!" is good for this). We will attack you,
cover you with blood, shred your clothes, and slip you a makeup kit so you
can create new zombies. If you want to show up already in zombie gear,
great. Just join the mob at any time.

Rules - Don't attack people who haven't clearly indicated they want to be
attacked. Don't get blood on bystanders or their things.

Subject: [sfraves] bsp: Tonight! London's Brian Aneurysm takes [KONTROL]!!!

Episode 15!  Can you believe it?

We're looking forward to another killer show!

Expect some deep, dark, heavy, pretty and intense minimal techno and
tech-house blended together in a very unique way.  Fans of our Troy
Pierce show in January will definitely dig!  If you're not afraid of a
little darkness in your funk, you're in for quite a treat. Make sure
to check out the ridiculously awesome EchoPilot track (in the audio
section below) to get a taste of what you're in for.

Also of note is that the art this month is really worth seeing!  Great stuff.

Hope to see some of you there.

____________________________________


Saturday, August 19

[ K O N T R O L ]

minimal techno + avant house
every 3rd Saturday at Rx Gallery


featuring from London in his SF debut:


BRIAN ANEURYSM   (aka EchoPilot)

iron box . spectral . poker flat . traum . sub-static
morris audio . immigrant . triebstoff . tic tac toe

Raised in Vienna and schooled in the ways of quality techno in Dallas
in the late 90's, Bernhard Pucher has been DJing and producing for
some of the world's most respected labels (including his own Iron Box
Music) for nearly a decade. These days he lives in London and, when
not performing throughout the world, creates electro/industrial-tinged
tracks as Confutatis, moody minimal techno as EchoPilot, and
deliciously sinister dancefloor tech-house as Brian Aneurysm. Catch
his unique style in this SF debut performance.  www.briananeurysm.com


plus special guest just added!


JASON SHORT  (aka Sattva)

funkycozy . coalition of the killing . auralism records

Recent Miami transplant Jason Short (formerly known as Sattva) caught
our attention last year when we heard some of his outstanding DJ
mixes.  His heady, deep, and dirty blend of minimal and tech-house has
landed him recent slots opening for Damian Lazarus and DJ Traxx, as
well as a permanent spot on the always-solid FunkyCozy roster, the
collective that's brought SF the likes of Pier Bucci, Matt Tolfrey,
Damian Lazarus and many more.  www.funkycozy.com


with [KONTROL] residents:

ALLAND BYALLO  ( liebe*detail . kvadrat produkt . mo's ferry )
SAMMY D  ( classic . dirtybird . utensil )
CRAIG KUNA   ( concept sf . esdjco )


Rx Gallery art exhibition:  Uplifting Vengeance 2006 World Tour

The art this month is INTENSE!  Don't miss it.

Check out a sneak peek here:
http://www.rxgallery.com/images/artistworks/skinner.jpg

==== BIOGRAPHIES ====


BRIAN ANEURYSM

Bernhard Pucher has been producing electronic music for almost a
decade.  He started buying records in '96 and ended up getting into
production within the same year.  Inspired by the local dance
community, he started working on his craft in his home town of Vienna,
Austria.  In 1998, he moved to Dallas, Texas where he experienced a
completely new environment for electronic music.  He met a lot of
people who were not just into dance, but also into more experimental
forms of electronica, including down tempo, industrial, breaks, and
hard techno.  This new environment shaped his style, and with the help
of his friend Stefan Anion, he started getting into playing live as
well.  But by 2000, a drastic shift happened. He started teaming up
with mutual techno lover Eric Estornel (aka Maetrik, Mariel Ito) who
then introduced him to a form of music he had not properly experienced
until then: Minimal and Electro. That influenced his musical style so
much that by 2001 he started his own label IRON BOX MUSIC. With his
background in industrial and heavy metal, his minimal sound started to
take shape in its own way.  In 2005, his journey brought him to
London, by then with many releases, remixes and appearances under his
belt on labels like Ai Records, Sub-Static, Spectral, Traum, Morris
Audio, Ware, Onitor, Poker Flat, Tangent Beats, and of course his own
label, Iron Box Music.


JASON SHORT

Jason Short began spinning and producing underground dance music in
1997 in San Francisco.  He soon after relocated to Florida, where he
earned a degree in Recording Engineering and began producing with some
friends as Biogenesis.  His productions caught the attention of
Xplosion and Nepol Records, and eight releases and several remixes
followed. After obtaining his degree, Jason wanted to return to the
roots of house music and moved to Chicago in 2001.  Inspired and
focused, he flourished in the studio and soon found himself djing all
over Chicago.  In 2002, Jason met Hac Le while fighting over the same
vinyl at world famous Gramaphone Records. The two immediately formed a
synergistic musical bond and began dropping mean 2x6x2 (2 mixers 6
turntables 2 djs) tag-team sets which quickly gained them critical
acclaim and a monthly residency in Mexico City with Global Trip.  In
2003, Jason headed to Miami to reconnect with Marc Smith of Biognesis
and work on their next project, Coaltion of the Killing, and develop
their new label, Auralism Records.  He has spent the past two years
honing his skills as a musician, dj, producer, and engineer, traveling
regularly to play with the FunkyCozy crew in San Francisco.  His
vibrations from the decks range from twisted, bass-heavy, floor-moving
techno to flowing, melodic, glitchy downtempo and experimental.  The
sounds are psychedelic and deep, glistening with serotonin-inducing
shimmers and infectious rhythms that push your body into motion.
