==== AUDIO ====

EchoPilot - Emptiness (sample)   (...a KONTROL favorite!)
http://www.kontrolsf.com/AUD/EchoPilot_-_Emptiness.mp3

Brian Aneurysm - Iron Box Sessions #13 (DJ set)
http://www.ironboxmusic.com/audio/brian_aneurysm_IBS13.mp3


==== REVIEWS ====

Brian Aneurysm - Succubus - Sub-Static

Sub Static return with humorously named Brian Aneurysm who drops 4
tracks of straight up techno hijinks for the heads. Brian hails from
Texas - past releases have been on his own, so hot it hurts, Iron Box
techouse label, as well as Poker Flat and Ware. After his venomously
brilliant double ep "Amplified" (sub static #28), the Texan has now
upgraded his sharp-edged techno funk wrecks to an ugly assed nasty
jacker on the title cut, which doesn't even have to be played
backwards to spread its seductive poison. Diabolic stuff, and great
material for the more darkside inclined clubsound. Damaging.

Echopilot - Fragile EP - Morris Audio CitySport Edition

Produced by Brian Pucher (aka Brian Aneurysm) under his Echopilot
guise, this is akin to taking one part minimal Richie Hawtin and one
part quirky Derrick Carter and one part silky Timewriter; and blending
them together into a deep, minimal concoction.  Simple rhythms,
eclectic (and sometimes disturbing) vocal samples, jazzy stabs and a
ton of atmosphere come together to take you on a journey through the
mind of a mad scientist. This is about as funky and tricked out as
anything you are likely to hear, and one of the best productions of
the year to this point. Exquisite Stuff.

Brian Aneurysm - The End of Logic - Iron Box Music

Bernard Pucher comes back under his alias Brian Aneurysm, opening the
year harder than ever before with a minimal techno stomper. He is
known for his dark and twisted minimal, but on this record, he
combines that with his love for good old techno, and creates an
energy-laden EP called THE END OF LOGIC. The original is distorted,
thick and crunchy with a twisted vocal ...you know, the kind we've
come to love from Brian Aneurysm. The B-Side offers 2dollarEgg-style
thump tracks that combine great production with minimal flavour
resulting in dancefloor mania.

O'Farrel. We'll Pick up stragglers at Union Square by 3:30p. See the <
http://eatbrains.com/mob2006/images/mobmap.jpg>Map

How to participate: Plant yourself somewhere along our route. Show up in
plain clothes minus anything of value. Wear a small piece of duct tape (or
similar) clearly visible on your torso. Attract our attention somehow.
(screaming "aaaiiieeee! zombies!" is good for this). We will attack you,
cover you with blood, shred your clothes, and slip you a makeup kit so you
can create new zombies. If you want to show up already in zombie gear,
great. Just join the mob at any time.

Rules - Don't attack people who haven't clearly indicated they want to be
attacked. Don't get blood on bystanders or their things.

>On August 21, 2005 my father died. He was a great and gentle man who left his mark on the world forever. During the past year my family and I have discussed many ways in which we could carry on his work and his legacy. 
>
>We have decided to establish the Bob Moog Memorial Foundation for Electronic Music, with a few carefully chosen objectives, each tied to his life and work.
>
>Today, we invite you to join us. Please visit our new website <http://www.moogfoundation.org>www.moogfoundation.org 
>

>

"Americans like to talk about (or be told about) Democracy but, when put to the test, usually find it to be an 'inconvenience.' We have opted instead for an authoritarian system disguised as a Democracy. We pay through the nose for an enormous joke-of-a-government, let it push us around, and then wonder how all those assholes got in there." - Frank Zappa 

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

On August 21, 2005 my father died. He was a great and gentle man who left
his mark on the world forever. During the past year my family and I have
discussed many ways in which we could carry on his work and his legacy.
<br><br>
We have decided to establish the Bob Moog Memorial Foundation for
Electronic Music, with a few carefully chosen objectives, each tied to
his life and work.<br><br>
Today, we invite you to join us. Please visit our new website
<a href="http://www.moogfoundation.org">www.moogfoundation.org</a>
<br><br>
Sincerely, <br><br>
Michelle Moog-Koussa<br>
Director, The Bob Moog Foundation <br>
&nbsp;
<img src="cid:7.0.1.0.2.20060821135619.03241480@speakeasy.org.1" width=160 height=31 alt="[]">
&nbsp;&nbsp; <br><br>
&nbsp;<br><br>
Our Goals<br><br>
The Foundation has set forth the following as its initial objectives: 
<ul>
<li>Endowed Scholarships 
<li>The Bob Moog Memorial Museum 
<li>Outreach Programs for Disadvantaged Students 
<li>Special Events for Electronic Music 
</ul><br>
<a href="http://www.moogfoundation.org">Read more... </a><br>
&nbsp;
<img src="cid:7.0.1.0.2.20060821135619.03241480@speakeasy.org.1" width=160 height=31 alt="[]">
&nbsp;&nbsp; <br><br>
&nbsp;<br><br>
MoogCasts | Documentary Podcast <br><br>
We're developing a documentary series that features artists playing Moog
Music instruments. <br><br>
This first episode features Perpetual Groove, a rock n' roll band, with
every member playing at least one Moog. <br><br>
What's a podcast? That's on the site, too. <br><br>
<a href="http://www.moogfoundation.org/content/view/37/52/">Listen now...
</a><br>
&nbsp;
<img src="cid:7.0.1.0.2.20060821135619.03241480@speakeasy.org.1" width=160 height=31 alt="[]">
&nbsp;&nbsp; <br><br>
&nbsp;<br><br>
Supporting the Foundation<br><br>
We have vision. We have determination. To carry out our intentions to
honor Bob’s legacy, we need money.<br><br>
Please consider making a contribution to our Foundation. You may choose
to give now, or make a pledge to give over time. Every contribution
counts.<br><br>
We also need you to spread the word--forward this email to friends,
colleagues, and anyone interested in the work and legacy of Dr. Bob Moog.
<br><br>
<a href="https://secure.groundspring.org/dn/index.php?aid=11672">Support

Subject: [sfraves] Tranceportal day party thanks

Hi everybody!

We wanted to send our thanks to everybody who came out to hang with us last
last week in a meadow full of trance.  Somewhere around 2-3pm a bunch of you
came by, and with your help we were able to raise $350 to help out Josh Wolf
(http://freejosh.pbwiki.com) which we have already sent to Liz.

The website has been updated with party photos and recordings of all the
DJs.  Visit http://www.tranceportal.org, you'll find them in the events
section.  Thanks Skye and Evi for all the photos we were able to add into
the gallery!

It was great to seeing so many old friends and tons of new faces, we had a
lot of fun and hope to do it again soon!

--
Colin/Paul/Addison
http://www.tranceportal.org

Subject: [sfraves] Oh Yeah.. quick WR of last weekend :)

So last Saturday was kinda upsetting, but like mondo fulfiling @ the same
time :)  Like I got flaked on hardcore not once, but twice by the same
person who said that I could work for him so i could make some fast cash
by helping him clean like these mansions in Fairfield.. la la la... then
he was gonna take me up to SAc & I was suppose 2 go 2 Heavyweights that
Drop Heavy was throwin', but oh well... never happened...

So anywaze.. there's somethning I'm involved in right now TV show-wise i'm
not allowed to talk about yet... but like the Executive Producer called me
Sat evening & told me that I was gonna be working on that night, so score
:)  YAY!!!

So the 1st place we shot was @ BamBuhda Lounge (Phoenix Hotel) wherre
there was a SF House Collective Fund raiser shindig & I interviewed the
promoter Scott.. it was a Groovy shindig actually.. i mean.. outta all the
time i've been by that place.. i never went like inside 'cause i was like
promoting for 1015 dealie... but WOW... So nice!!! :)  It was funny.. like
i didn't expect to know anyone there.. then this girl like yelled my name
who I remember meeting from the old skool Blakes Ascension days... so that
was kinda Groovy.... I totally forgot her name... & it was hard to see who
she was in a 1/2 pitched dark room only lit up by din red lights... but
regardless... it was Dope seein' her again :)  LoL  Hello 2day :P

The next stop was SOMA-TECH :)  Now it took us a while to get there 'cause
it was @ a "hidden" underground location... now when they say Hidden...
they meant it... it took like an hour & 1/2 to find the location... like
me & the production crew went  to all the clubs were i knew the like
bouncers & they didn't even know where the street was... but like ok... it
was still Groovy catchin' up w/ them 'cause it's been rare that I been in
SOMA lately.. lol... oh yeah.. i even saw Oli & Big J @ Butter, but they
had no clue what i was lookin' for...

So after Cat Club, 1015, Caliente, Paradise, we went to like DNA & I
talked to Barry there.. lol.. we went in the club & did a google serch..
Hello 2day.. we found it!  So we got there... Hello 2Day.. it was the same
place where old skool SFR peeps Kimba & Seraphim used to live.. their old
wherehouse they used to live in :)

We kinda got there late... Catharsis spun already & Kuzse spun already..
so waaah :(  BUt when we got there... Christian Fuller (i think that was
him) was spinning this Yummy Techno... I mean.. it was kinda like Poppy
Misstress Barb kinda Techno... but it was fun!!!  LoL.. the dance floor
was packed & it was fun... saw sooooooooooooooo many old skool faces i
ain't seen in a loooong time there & it was fun hangin' out w/ a sloshed
Catharsis!!! :)  It was also fun makin' new Friends there which i really
hope to see again @ some point :)  Man... Awesome talks w/ people!!  I
mean... the attendance was probably more than it was suppose 2 B 'cause it
was in the Heart of SOMA.. the warehouse... so lik3e  I'm sure some like
passer byers like heard the Yummy Grooves & decided to check it out!!  But
it was really am Awesome crowd :)

Outta everywhere we been on Sat.. i only took picktures @ SOMA-TECH & i
kinda regret that :(  Oh Well... anywaze... here they go :)

http://s96.photobucket.com/albums/l188/YummyBeats/SOMA-TECH%208-20-2006/

I wish i made it on Sunday to the park... but yeah... my thoughts were
there :)  Love U Bam... Glad u had a Groovy Bday weekend dude :)

-- 


Take Care <3
Peace=->Jus' Me =-> O§bY {8O)

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: UPDATE!!!! THE PHAT CONDUCTOR joining us at Crooked tomorrow!

(This is straight from my fellow Renegade Ferret Evinrude...)

Oh man! Gotta love the last minute 
international-peeps-in-town-for-Burning-Man sets, right?

Needless to say, we're pretty damn stoked to be hosting The Phat Conductor 
at Nickie's tomorrow. This 2Wars/A Revolution Records recording artist (and 
one of Urb Magazine's "Next 100" picks) is one of Toronto, Canada's leading 
figures in breaks, regularly doing gigs in Canada, the UK and the US. He'll 
be doing a live laptop set at Crooked.

>From his site (thephatconductor.com - check it for some mixes, too...): "Old 
School, Nu Skool, Home School... it doesn't matter. With an ear for the 
future and an eye on the dancefloor the man behind Ice-9 brings you lush, 
organic electronics, funky bass grooves and a live performance to tell your 
grandkids about..."

So yeah, this is AWESOME! Come check it!

And on top of all that, the original plan is still in effect, as well. I 
certainly don't want to overshadow the fact that Aaron Jae and Donna Matrix 
are gonna be in the house as well. They're two of my favorite DJs around, so 
all in all, all I can say is "Damn. Now THIS is a Wednesday night lineup!"


Crooked
Wednesday, 8/23
Nickie's BBQ, 460 Haight St. @ Fillmore, SF
10pm-2am
$3, 21+ with ID

4. *Bridge = Doom Selector - Broken Joint (The Phat Conductor Edit)
5. Docta Seuss + The Phat Conductor - Untitled - Unsigned
6. Bassnectar + The Phat Conductor - Ancient Astronauts - Unsigned
7. Prosper and Balda - D'All Ass (Bassbin Twins Remix) - Funky Cactus
8. Rawhill Cru - Jungle Ain't Sellin' (Dave Dub + The Phat Conductor's Funk
mix) - Funky Cactus (Forthcoming)
9. *Bridge = James Brown - Payback Megamix (The Phat Conductor Edit) -
Bootleg
10. Beck - High Five vs. Dubplate Culture (The Phat Conductor Remix) -
Bootleg
11. The Phat Conductor's Chocolate Salty Balls
12. Price Cuts - That's Right (Dave Dub + The Phat Conductor Remix) -
Lab-Rok (Forthcoming)
13. Robb G + The Phat Conductor - Chunkasaurus - Menu Music (Forthcoming)
14. Rawhill Cru - Jungle Ain't Sellin' (Dave Dub + The Phat Conductor's
Breaks Mix) - Funky Cactus (Forthcoming)
15. Steelzawheelz - Discotron (Drummatic Twins Mix) - Money Shot
16. Geek Ghastly - Rage Against Terror - Bootleg
17. The Phat Conductor - Ice-9 - 2Wars
18. Guru and the Roots - Lift Your Fist (Wayward Soul Bootleg)
19. Raster - The Prototype (Tipper's Tippy Bazmeg Remix) - Chi Records
20. Raster - Spiral Transform - Chi Records
21. The Nam Shub of Enki - Phresch Controller - Unreleased

  b=SyyL6l1zTGZyqITzxN+tF114yZeQnjnUQZrMEBCqf7iUwPSco3S7bm8o5yJ7/laU5OuIihlqfw1W7HfCHH82JyJt70QL2XBRe6betgKusBR0fg+Bjz6aCJN13neh0rgVxJ3ipSl/km0PPZD8Xp3GMdBiHUOmBMNlSVp7mo734co=  ;
Message-ID: <20060823043317.56039.qmail@web32407.mail.mud.yahoo.com>
Date: Tue, 22 Aug 2006 21:33:17 -0700 (PDT)
From: <dangrsmind@yahoo.com>
Reply-To: dangrsmind@yahoo.com
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=us-ascii
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: [sfraves] weekend report (of sorts)

Hi All,

My wife and I finally made it out this past weekend.   Unfortunately because of the logistics of getting a babysitter we don't always have a choice about what night to go out.  That meant missing Mighty Breaks on Friday, and so we decided to attend a Sunset/GGL (Green Gorilla Lounge) "underground" called Fully Loaded at Gingerbread.

Now I don't want to be accused of being hater here.  I consider myself to mostly be a house head, so I was looking forward to this party.  I've been a fan of both crews for years and I've attended numerous Sunset and GGL parties previously.  However, I did not like this party.  The venue was alright, featuring relatively safe parking ($3) across the street, decent bathrooms and acceptable sound.  When we got there M3 was spinning some half decent house.  I enjoyed the projections and so forth.  But it wasn't too crowded and the vibe wasn't really clicking.  

After a while of chilling, it was time for one of the bands, Bobbie Marie, to play.  I'm pretty openminded musically and I like a lot of different styles.  I like live percussion and instruments at aprties too.  However, I don't know if I just didn't get this band, but I thought they were awful.  Sort of bad industrial/punk crossed with Devo-esque vocals also done badly.  Almost immediately the downstairs dance floor was cleared,and we (and most everyone else) fled upstairs where Sharon Buck was spinning some nice funky tracks.  People upstairs were dancing while the hideous grating of nails and chalkboards continued downstairs.  For a bit it seemed like the upstairs might go off, but then suddenly the crowd began to thin out.  Apparently the downstairs was now open again as the second band, Landshark, set up.  We migrated downstairs, hoping the vibe would solidfy, but it just was even more diffused.  We decided to leave and go elsewhere.

Headed over towards the Aspire 8 yr. party which we found easily.  While looking for parking we saw a lot of very sketchy characters leaving the venue and lurking around the side streets in the area.  I didn't really think parking there was such a great plan. We were probably over reacting, but we decided to move on anyway.  I headed for Kontrol over at the Rx Gallery, but it was after 3AM and by this point and my navigation abilities were shot.  I couldn't find the Rx.  And my GPS navigation system seemed more like the controls of an alien spacecraft than anything else. After a few minuted of futile searching in the Tenderloin, we realized that the CD in my car was sounding REAL GOOD right about then.  So we decided to head for the beach and just enjoy the rest of the evening/morning sans party.

Ok, we had a good time anyway, but this wasn't a good party. In fact I'd say it was a good example of how to have a bad party.  Wrong people, wrong music, wrong venue.  Timing of set changes badly managed.  Weird drink system that encouraged people to drink more than they should (you had to buy 3 drinks at a time for $10 including juice, water, soda, etc.)  Bleh.  I liked the venue however.

We had intended to head over to Golden Gate Park for Shishkabeats Sunday, but we were so sleepy.  Yawn.  We could hardly... Yawn... get out of bed.  Yawn. Snore.

Peace,

Peter




---------------------------------------------------------------------
To unsubscribe, e-mail: sfraves-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org
For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Subject: Re: [sfraves] weekend report (of sorts)

Well right.  

I like Lance Desardi's mixes and some of his tracks.  I've heard some Landshark remixes that I liked.  But by the time they were setting up, we were ready to leave.  The party wasn't going anywhere.  So in the end I didn't hear Landshark.

The whole scene reminded me of this party we had in college circa 1980 called the Step On My Face party aka Beat Me, Fuck Me, Make Me Write Bad Checks.  There were even some guys in drag, but I didn't get the impression that they were actually drag queens.  It was more of a put on or something. 

Peter

----- Original Message ----
From: Van Mundegaarde <electrofunk138@hotmail.com>

Subject: RE: [sfraves] weekend report (of sorts)

The 1st band you described sounds like pretty much every band/sound that 
gets played over at the Rickshaw. I highly recommend that NO ONE ever goes 
to that hipster nightmare of a place.

Landshark - that's Lance Desardi's band. Wewre they worth a fuck, or just as 
lame as "band # 1" ?




>From: <dangrsmind@yahoo.com>
>Reply-To: dangrsmind@yahoo.com
>To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
>Subject: [sfraves] weekend report (of sorts)
>Date: Tue, 22 Aug 2006 21:33:17 -0700 (PDT)
>
>Hi All,
>
>My wife and I finally made it out this past weekend.   Unfortunately 
>because of the logistics of getting a babysitter we don't always have a 
>choice about what night to go out.  That meant missing Mighty Breaks on 
>Friday, and so we decided to attend a Sunset/GGL (Green Gorilla Lounge) 
>"underground" called Fully Loaded at Gingerbread.
>
>Now I don't want to be accused of being hater here.  I consider myself to 
>mostly be a house head, so I was looking forward to this party.  I've been 
>a fan of both crews for years and I've attended numerous Sunset and GGL 
>parties previously.  However, I did not like this party.  The venue was 
>alright, featuring relatively safe parking ($3) across the street, decent 
>bathrooms and acceptable sound.  When we got there M3 was spinning some 
>half decent house.  I enjoyed the projections and so forth.  But it wasn't 
>too crowded and the vibe wasn't really clicking.
>
>After a while of chilling, it was time for one of the bands, Bobbie Marie, 
>to play.  I'm pretty openminded musically and I like a lot of different 
>styles.  I like live percussion and instruments at aprties too.  However, I 
>don't know if I just didn't get this band, but I thought they were awful.  
>Sort of bad industrial/punk crossed with Devo-esque vocals also done badly. 
>  Almost immediately the downstairs dance floor was cleared,and we (and 
>most everyone else) fled upstairs where Sharon Buck was spinning some nice 
>funky tracks.  People upstairs were dancing while the hideous grating of 
>nails and chalkboards continued downstairs.  For a bit it seemed like the 
>upstairs might go off, but then suddenly the crowd began to thin out.  
>Apparently the downstairs was now open again as the second band, Landshark, 
>set up.  We migrated downstairs, hoping the vibe would solidfy, but it just 
>was even more diffused.  We decided to leave and go elsewhere.
>
>Headed over towards the Aspire 8 yr. party which we found easily.  While 
>looking for parking we saw a lot of very sketchy characters leaving the 
>venue and lurking around the side streets in the area.  I didn't really 
>think parking there was such a great plan. We were probably over reacting, 
>but we decided to move on anyway.  I headed for Kontrol over at the Rx 
>Gallery, but it was after 3AM and by this point and my navigation abilities 
>were shot.  I couldn't find the Rx.  And my GPS navigation system seemed 
>more like the controls of an alien spacecraft than anything else. After a 
>few minuted of futile searching in the Tenderloin, we realized that the CD 
>in my car was sounding REAL GOOD right about then.  So we decided to head 
>for the beach and just enjoy the rest of the evening/morning sans party.
>
>Ok, we had a good time anyway, but this wasn't a good party. In fact I'd 
>say it was a good example of how to have a bad party.  Wrong people, wrong 
>music, wrong venue.  Timing of set changes badly managed.  Weird drink 
>system that encouraged people to drink more than they should (you had to 
>buy 3 drinks at a time for $10 including juice, water, soda, etc.)  Bleh.  
>I liked the venue however.
>
>We had intended to head over to Golden Gate Park for Shishkabeats Sunday, 
>but we were so sleepy.  Yawn.  We could hardly... Yawn... get out of bed.  
>Yawn. Snore.
>
>Peace,
>
>Peter
>
>
>
>
>---------------------------------------------------------------------
>To unsubscribe, e-mail: sfraves-unsubscribe@hyperreal.org
>For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org
>

Actually the members of Bobbie Marie & Landshark were mostly the same. A few
guitarists less for Landshark, and Lance doing vocals instead of keyboards.

I have to say, it was what I'd call "hipster house." Landshark was pretty OK
- they did play "tie me up" which of course, rocked. Sadly, they played that
towards the end of their set, and after a lot of my friends had  left. Alas.

The music picked up a lot after that - Anthony was dropping the heat and
then galen finished up (and played a track that anthony had just played 20
minutes prior).

I looked for you to say Hi, but the guy in the orange shirt said his name
was not Peter, but could be whatever I wanted it to be. After that I gave
up.

Yep, the drink situation was pretty wonky, but with a few friends, we all
kept nicely toasted. I rocked my earplugs, and I had a pretty good time
overall.


~juju

Subject: Re: [sfraves] weekend report (of sorts)

Actually the members of Bobbie Marie & Landshark were mostly the same. A few
guitarists less for Landshark, and Lance doing vocals instead of keyboards.

I have to say, it was what I'd call "hipster house." Landshark was pretty OK
- they did play "tie me up" which of course, rocked. Sadly, they played that
towards the end of their set, and after a lot of my friends had  left. Alas.

The music picked up a lot after that - Anthony was dropping the heat and
then galen finished up (and played a track that anthony had just played 20
minutes prior).

I looked for you to say Hi, but the guy in the orange shirt said his name
was not Peter, but could be whatever I wanted it to be. After that I gave
up.

Yep, the drink situation was pretty wonky, but with a few friends, we all
kept nicely toasted. I rocked my earplugs, and I had a pretty good time
overall.


~juju

On 8/23/06, dangrsmind@yahoo.com <dangrsmind@yahoo.com> wrote:
>
> Well right.
>
> I like Lance Desardi's mixes and some of his tracks.  I've heard some

> were ready to leave.  The party wasn't going anywhere.  So in the end I

> >From: <dangrsmind@yahoo.com>
> >Reply-To: dangrsmind@yahoo.com
> >To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
> >Subject: [sfraves] weekend report (of sorts)
> >Date: Tue, 22 Aug 2006 21:33:17 -0700 (PDT)
> >
> >Hi All,
> >
> >My wife and I finally made it out this past weekend.   Unfortunately
> >because of the logistics of getting a babysitter we don't always have a
> >choice about what night to go out.  That meant missing Mighty Breaks on
> >Friday, and so we decided to attend a Sunset/GGL (Green Gorilla Lounge)
> >"underground" called Fully Loaded at Gingerbread.
> >
> >Now I don't want to be accused of being hater here.  I consider myself to
> >mostly be a house head, so I was looking forward to this party.  I've
> been
> >a fan of both crews for years and I've attended numerous Sunset and GGL
> >parties previously.  However, I did not like this party.  The venue was
> >alright, featuring relatively safe parking ($3) across the street, decent
> >bathrooms and acceptable sound.  When we got there M3 was spinning some
> >half decent house.  I enjoyed the projections and so forth.  But it
> wasn't
> >too crowded and the vibe wasn't really clicking.
> >
> >After a while of chilling, it was time for one of the bands, Bobbie
> Marie,
> >to play.  I'm pretty openminded musically and I like a lot of different
> >styles.  I like live percussion and instruments at aprties too.  However,
> I
> >don't know if I just didn't get this band, but I thought they were awful.
> >Sort of bad industrial/punk crossed with Devo-esque vocals also done
> badly.
> >  Almost immediately the downstairs dance floor was cleared,and we (and
> >most everyone else) fled upstairs where Sharon Buck was spinning some
> nice
> >funky tracks.  People upstairs were dancing while the hideous grating of
> >nails and chalkboards continued downstairs.  For a bit it seemed like the
> >upstairs might go off, but then suddenly the crowd began to thin out.
> >Apparently the downstairs was now open again as the second band,
> Landshark,
> >set up.  We migrated downstairs, hoping the vibe would solidfy, but it
> just
> >was even more diffused.  We decided to leave and go elsewhere.
> >
> >Headed over towards the Aspire 8 yr. party which we found easily.  While
> >looking for parking we saw a lot of very sketchy characters leaving the
> >venue and lurking around the side streets in the area.  I didn't really
> >think parking there was such a great plan. We were probably over
> reacting,
> >but we decided to move on anyway.  I headed for Kontrol over at the Rx
> >Gallery, but it was after 3AM and by this point and my navigation
> abilities
> >were shot.  I couldn't find the Rx.  And my GPS navigation system seemed
> >more like the controls of an alien spacecraft than anything else. After a
> >few minuted of futile searching in the Tenderloin, we realized that the
> CD
> >in my car was sounding REAL GOOD right about then.  So we decided to head
> >for the beach and just enjoy the rest of the evening/morning sans party.
> >
> >Ok, we had a good time anyway, but this wasn't a good party. In fact I'd
> >say it was a good example of how to have a bad party.  Wrong people,
> wrong
> >music, wrong venue.  Timing of set changes badly managed.  Weird drink
> >system that encouraged people to drink more than they should (you had to
> >buy 3 drinks at a time for $10 including juice, water, soda, etc.)  Bleh.
> >I liked the venue however.
> >
> >We had intended to head over to Golden Gate Park for Shishkabeats Sunday,
> >but we were so sleepy.  Yawn.  We could hardly... Yawn... get out of bed.
> >Yawn. Snore.
> >
> >Peace,
> >
> >Peter
> >
> >

Hey man, I'm the one that started this thread, and I will admit that I don't
know Karina well at all.

All I know is that I saw what looked to possibly be a suicide note and
thought it better to be safe than sorry.

>From what I do know of Karina, I agree she doesn't at all seem the type to
just give up.  But that's exactly what I thought of my highschool Humanities
teacher too.  Depression and circumstance have ways of clouding
otherwise healthy minds.

let us not forget this is a human being's life we're talking about.

at the loss of a loved one and the fact that no one cared enough to try to
do something about it.

Do you not agree?

Concentrating on the basic element of life: air/breath and synapse firing
their pulses of electricity, the loud thought flying by, getting deeper with
every looping rhythm. The noise of life suddenly makes the basics disappear

doesn't seem to help, if anything just amplify my emotions. I am five blocks
away from returning to dxm after being sober for the last year and a half
sitting here with pinkeye in both eyes, a fever, soar throat, and lack of
will to live. Being dissociated would be a lovely way to die,



but not today.

  Hey man, I'm the one that started this thread, and I will admit that I don't know Karina well at all.

  All I know is that I saw what looked to possibly be a suicide note and thought it better to be safe than sorry.

  From what I do know of Karina, I agree she doesn't at all seem the type to just give up.  But that's exactly what I thought of my highschool Humanities teacher too.  Depression and circumstance have ways of clouding otherwise healthy minds. 

  I'm willing to wager 90% odds that this was just a hack or a cruel joke, but let us not forget this is a human being's life we're talking about.

  I'd rather you be disappointed that someone over-reacted than be heartbroken at the loss of a loved one and the fact that no one cared enough to try to do something about it.

  Do you not agree?

I got this from her in a bulk a few weeks ago:

z0phreak0z:  I hope all is well with you and I  give you much wishes for 
happiness and peace. I'm moving on the 31st and may be without internet 
access for a bit. My exact destination is not determined at the moment 
though I will hopefully will be settled over the next month or so.  I can 
be reached at karina@area.com and 650.716.7169 - keep in mind there may be 
some delay in my responses but I'll do my best to get back to you. Have a 
wonderful weekend and thanks for your friendship. I send you much love 
always in all ways and Namaste!!!!

On the 15th I got a Happy B-Day message (my internet B-Day)

I think the Irony is that when she tries to do something nice for people, 
she get's berrated, shot down, belittled, and made to feel like the lowest 
form of life on the planet.

Yet, if people think she might kill herself (why on earth would she 
POSSIBLY want to do that) then suddenly everyone cares and shows 
concern.  Did anyone care 6 months ago when she lost her job?  Did anyone 
care when her health wa sin shambles?  Anyone bother to call when she had a 
working phone?

Well, as I said I don't know Karina and I've in fact only met her once.  If you are refering to the "SFraves benefit" I don't agree with everything you did regarding that  or how that was approached.   But that doesn't mean I wished her illwill or that I  didn't try to help her.  As it so happens I did pass her resume on to the hiring manager for a QA position at my company.  They hired someone else recently and weren't looking to hire anyone at this time.  But I passed it on anyway.  FWIW my current job doesn't involve hiring or managing people so I couldn't help directly.  

I've repeatedly tried to help people on this list when they were unemployed or looking for better gigs.  The people I've offered help to know this is true.  I've been there myself not long ago and I resolved to try and help others because no one tried to help me.

My employer is not currently hiring since the company actually will run out of funding at the end of November,  but if anyone sees any jobs they are interested in at Stanford University, especially the Stanford Graduate School of Business, please let me know.  My wife works there and we'll try to help.  Naturally I can't promise anything and you'll still ahve to go through the interview process etc.

I've previously posted this offer to the list at least twice.

If you were a real 'raver' you'd give a rats ass who was there or why they 
were there. You'd be there for what ever reasons you were there. Period. Don't 
judge and don't be judged. My personal perspective is its all about the music. 
You don't know them and they don't know you. How do you know they are there or 
are into the scene to "see and be seen"? When I was on the list way back in 
the day, everyone I met in person from the list use to think the same damn 
thing about me. Until they got to know me. Everyone thought I was a pretty boy. I 
am, but that doesn't define who I am. Good people and bad people run in all 
circles, including ravers, house heads, trance babies, etc...

Point is, make a conscious decision to be different. Don't be like that. Its 
just a pet peeve of mine and a big turn off. There have been so many people 
who have come in and out of my life that if I had stopped to judge I would have 
never been blessed with what they had to contribute to me. You might find a 
diamond in the rough also.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Karina

Your point about not judging people?  I got the point.  

I know Marco so I know that's not how he his or what he was saying.  Maybe you are being judgemental yourself?

Haven't you ever encountered people that thought they were too cool, too hip, just too damn good looking, to even appear slightly to be having a good time at a club or party?  Maybe they really are having a party in their pants, but the rest of us will never know.  I find it to be somewhat of a downer personally to be around a bunch of people with dour faces at a party.

If I notice this situation, and don't find it enjoyable, does that automatically make me judgemental?  Hmm.

In another online community I belong to there is a saying "Assume goodwill."  The idea is that in the absence of strong proof to the contrary, one should always assume good will from others in the community.  But the idea of assume goodwill cuts both ways.  Your are right that we should assume goodwill from the utlra cool posers and pseudo-hipsters that wouldn't give many people on this list the time of day.  After all they are probably just lonely and looking for a real human connection, but totally clueless about how to find one and afraid to find out what would happen if they did.  

But by the same argument we should assume goodwill from those that criticize them.  They're just practicing discriminating awareness.  

I've found "assume goodwill" to be a very challenging and insightful little mantra.  Try it yourself and you might find the same.

Peace,

Peter

Well, wow.  I guess we don't see eye to eye.  

I never said I was judging anyone by their clothes or their skin or their gender.  You just sort of made that part up didn't you?  What I'm talking about is people's attitude.

I don't care if you are black, asian, a middle aged white guy (like me) or whatever.  I don't care if you're gay or straight, tall or short.  So long as you are there to have a good time.  I wish there were more wildly mixed parties than there are mostly these days actually.

Part of the reason I go to parties is to meet and dance with other people from all walks of life.  Its not at all about being focused on my self as you put it.  In fact, for me its totally the opposite.

One of the best things I've gotten from dance culture, both at both raves and clubs, is that I've gotten to meet and dance with all different types of people froma ll over the world.  The reason I go out rather than staying home and playing records myself is these other people.

What I'm saying is that if people aren't at a party to have a good time, if they're posing or just there to show off their clothes or get laid or get drunk/wasted, if they're already drunk/wasted and aggresive out of control, or simply tired and depressed for whatever reason, if the flow and set timing of the music are off, if there's just no energy in the room, then its probably not going to be a very fun party.   Still I'll always give it a go.  But personally after a few hours of that I'm going to be further on up the road.  If that makes me jaded, then so be it.

Peace,

Peter

 In a message dated 8/23/06 9:19:26 PM, dangrsmind@yahoo.com writes:
 
 
 Your point about not judging people?  I got the point. 
 
 Excellent!   But that really wasn't my point. My point was more to focus on ones self rather than others. 
 
 
 I know Marco so I know that's not how he his or what he was saying.  Maybe you are being judgemental yourself?
 
 Please explain how I'm being judgemental?
 
 Haven't you ever encountered people that thought they were too cool, too hip, just too damn good looking, to even appear slightly to be having a good time at a club or party?  
 
 No, never. Why? Because I don't care nore do I judge people. I'm to busy dancing my ass off and vibing with my friends... I do find I don't like or care for people once I get to know them, but I never make judgement on them. Especially based on race, gender, clothing style, sexual preference, whether they are reall really good looking, what they drive, how much money they make, etc.... That could be construded as jealousy. 
 
 Maybe they really are having a party in their pants, but the rest of us will never know.  I find it to be somewhat of a downer personally to be around a bunch of people with dour faces at a party.
 
 This is all you. No response from me on this.... 
 
 If I notice this situation, and don't find it enjoyable, does that automatically make me judgemental?  Hmm.
 
 No, this doesn't make you judgemental. We all have preferences for our likes and dislikes. Its when we judge other people for thiers is when we are judgemental. I don't dig country music. But there are people who vibe off it much the same way I vibe on house. I don't have to like their music preferences, and I certainly have no right to judge them for theirs. 
 
 In another online community I belong to there is a saying "Assume goodwill."  The idea is that in the absence of strong proof to the contrary, one should always assume good will from others in the community.  
 
 This doesn't mean you have to embrace people just to assume goodwill.   I both club and rave. I dress the part of either. I've been accused of as you say being an "ultra cool posers and pseudo-hipsters". I'm don't even really know what that means. I laugh because its just pure ignorance. 
  
 But the idea of assume goodwill cuts both ways.  Your are right that we should assume goodwill from the utlra cool posers and pseudo-hipsters that wouldn't give many people on this list the time of day.  After all they are probably just lonely and looking for a real human connection, but totally clueless about how to find one and afraid to find out what would happen if they did. 
 
 How do you come to this conclusion another human is lonely or looking for real human connection just from looking at them? Who gives a shit if another assumes goodwill on you? I worry about whether or not I'm assuming goodwill on myself. I find this allows me to direct goodwill onto others without thinking about it naturally, and its usually waranted and appropriate. 
 
 But by the same argument we should assume goodwill from those that criticize them.  They're just practicing discriminating awareness. 
 
 Wrong, its just people being ignorant. Its perpectuating discrimanation, not praticing discrimanting awareness. In my eyes there is no such they as discriminating awareness. That could be a whole other discussion however. 
 
 I've found "assume goodwill" to be a very challenging and insightful little mantra.  Try it yourself and you might find the same.
 
 I guess the easy response to this would be to say rise above the challenge. I realize life is not always that simple. But we need to start somewhere. And that somewhere is within ourselves. Not within the judgement of others. Next time you find yourself in that situation, smile and remember why you are there at that particular moment, hopefully its the music!
 
 Peace,
 
 Peter
 
 A quick little story. I'm sitting in the parking lot a few weeks ago in my car waiting for my son. It was already dark, after 9:00pm. I was listening to some house music with my window down, not loud enough to hear very far from outside the car, if at all, and up walks this guy who asks me what I'm listening to. I told him and he offs his ear phones and says, here, listen to this. It was some crazy ass hip hop. Smoth, funky, and raw. It was this cats music. I laughed a little bit and asked, did you really expect me to be into hiphop? (I'm a middle aged white dude sitting in a family car, glasses on, having my nerd look going on). His reply was, most definately, I never judge a book by its cover. I bought his CD from him right then and there. $10. Simply out of respect for not judging me and having the heart to hustle for what he believed in. I dig the CD which is an added bonus. 
 
 When I first signed onto SF Raves back in 96 I remember my first post vividly. (Is Bodhi around still?) Bodhi sent out a thread talking about how he was scared by some mexican hoodlums as he stated. I ripped into him and started a huge flame war. Me being new to the list I got shit from every single member. That was, until I explained myself, and after me and Bodhi use to corresponde frequently as friends. 
 
 See, I was the only white kid who grew up in East Salinas. 100% of my friends at the time were Mexican. Just because someone is Mexican or dresses a certain way doesn't make them a hoodlum. Even if their dress style is gangster or cholo in someone elses eyes. I know plenty of cholo's who I would have in my home and trust with my life. Not because they'd shoot or kill for me, but because they are good people. I can't even begin to tell you what good food I use to eat from my friends moms when in their homes. Home made tortilla's are the shit........ Grow up.
 
 Peace, 
 
 M2

Well, depending on how you go about it.

At the party in question that spawned this thread, when I went to the bathroom for like 2 minutes, a guy had already moved in to try and hit on my wife.  And he wasn't like smiling or joking and happy about it.  When I came back he didn't smile and say, "My name is so and so, isn't it funny that I was trying to hit on your wife?" as frequently happens at parties inmy experience.  He just frowned and seemed angry.  Then he suddenly stood up and left.  He never said anything to either one of us.

Hassling women at parties is not cool.

I understand that the people that act this way are also suffering, but that doesn't mean I want to hang out with them.  You call that "judgemental", I call it discriminating wisdom.

Regards,

Peter

>goodwill."  The idea is that in the absence of strong proof to the 
>contrary, one should always assume good will from others in the community.
>
>  This doesn't mean you have to embrace people just to assume goodwill.   I 
>both club and rave. I dress the part of either. I've been accused of as you 
>say being an "ultra cool posers and pseudo-hipsters". I'm don't even really 
>know what that means. I laugh because its just pure ignorance.

>should assume goodwill from the utlra cool posers and pseudo-hipsters that

>clueless about how to find one and afraid to find out what would happen if 
>they did.
>
>  How do you come to this conclusion another human is lonely or looking for 
>real human connection just from looking at them? Who gives a shit if 
>another assumes goodwill on you? I worry about whether or not I'm assuming 
>goodwill on myself. I find this allows me to direct goodwill onto others 
>without thinking about it naturally, and its usually waranted and 
>appropriate.
>

>  I've found "assume goodwill" to be a very challenging and insightful 
>little mantra.  Try it yourself and you might find the same.
>
>  I guess the easy response to this would be to say rise above the 
>challenge. I realize life is not always that simple. But we need to start 
>somewhere. And that somewhere is within ourselves. Not within the judgement 
>of others. Next time you find yourself in that situation, smile and 
>remember why you are there at that particular moment, hopefully its the 
>music!

>very far from outside the car, if at all, and up walks this guy who asks me

>expect me to be into hiphop? (I'm a middle aged white dude sitting in a 
>family car, glasses on, having my nerd look going on). His reply was, most

>right then and there. $10. Simply out of respect for not judging me and

---

Good point:

The current SF definition of "hipster" is:

Skinny kids with vintage tees/levis/conductor hats/chucks/dunks/cut up goodwill clothes/funny haircuts/ironic moustaches or haute-couture versions of these (depending on the presence or absence of high-paying tech job/trust fund).  They listen to dance rock, minimal techno, electro-house, IDM-y pop and mashups and ride track bikes and mopeds around.  A lot of them are vegan, a lot of them eat giant steaks just to fuck with the vegan ones.

They are, by and large, nice, totally nonviolent (unless they're being violent in an ironic way), and mainly guilty of cliqueish behavior.  Their only "macho" issues are occasional beer/coke abuse spurred on by friends' excesses.

They are not the people hitting on anybody's wife, getting huffy on the dancefloor, or anything.  By and large, they're off having fun.  They u may act a little too cool for school now and then but they're not causing trouble.

The people Peter's talking about are.....

(wait for it...)

Guidos/Marina Men.  

BIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIIG difference.  These are the meatheads you speak of.

-G

desert or the forests).. it was unfortunately shut down before I started
partying in 95 but I hear it was quite the good time and a huge change
from church dances or tipping cows! ;)  My brother got to go but my
parents wouldn't let me go with him.  Pete also ran/runs XMission.  Utah's
biggest indie ISP.

Recently, President Bush notified the press that he would attend Orrin
Hatch's fundraiser dinner.  In response, Pete Ashdown is holding a dinner,
free of charge for 150 people at the Alta Club.  He says Bush and company
are welcome to attend it too.  This dinner is out of his own pocket and he
hopes that the people who come will donate a bunch of money to a charity
of their choice to combat hunger.  In fact, I think pretty much all of
Pete's campaign is being financed by himself.

-Rayn

> "Pete Ashdown: I have a friendship with Brian Behlendorf, who helped
> set up Wired's first venture on the internet, Hot Wired (now Wired
> News). He was also in charge of Organic and continues to be a member
> of the Apache Foundation -- a founding member of the Apache Foundation
> for that matter. And I initially knew him (from) the internet rave
> scene, because a lot of the early rave scene was connected through
> e-mail lists and the All Rave newsgroup, and of course there was a big
> concentration of that in San Francisco. So I came out to San Francisco
> frequently during that time."
>
>
> awesome.

> of these (depending on the presence or absence of high-paying tech job/trust
> fund).  They listen to dance rock, minimal techno, electro-house, IDM-y pop
> and mashups and ride track bikes and mopeds around.  A lot of them are
> vegan, a lot of them eat giant steaks just to fuck with the vegan ones.

> They are, by and large, nice, totally nonviolent (unless they're being
> violent in an ironic way), and mainly guilty of cliqueish behavior.  Their
> only "macho" issues are occasional beer/coke abuse spurred on by friends'
> excesses.
>

Power to the Peaceful 2006


On Saturday, September 9th, Musician and Filmmaker, Michael Franti and his group Spearhead with Guerrilla Management will present the 8th Annual 911 Power to the Peaceful Festival at Speedway Meadows in Golden Gate Park.  "Be Peace Now" is this year's theme.  In addition to the main stage of live music, PTTP also features morning yoga, an open-air art gallery, a healing arts tent, a DJ tent, vendors and food booths, an eco village, kid's zone, valet bike parking by the SF Bicycle Coalition, and  tabling and forums by social, environmental and political organizations.  A second stage has been added for this year.  The festival begins at 9am with morning yoga, and will last until 5pm.

http://www.indybay.org/newsitems/2006/08/22/18299893.php

that could be construed as selfish!

>>Haven't you ever encountered people that thought they were too 
>>cool, too hip, just too damn good looking, to even appear slightly 
>>to be having a good time at a club or party?
>
>No, never. Why? Because I don't care nore do I judge people. I'm to 
>busy dancing my ass off and vibing with my friends... I do find I 
>don't like or care for people once I get to know them, but I never 
>make judgement on them. Especially based on race, gender, clothing 
>style, sexual preference, whether they are reall really good 
>looking, what they drive, how much money they make, etc.... That 
>could be construded as jealousy.

I don't care that people own red cars.. but I still notice 
them.  Being observant isn't the same as being judgmental.  Being 
judgmental certainly doesn't necessitate jealousy, or vice versa.

>>Maybe they really are having a party in their pants, but the rest 
>>of us will never know.  I find it to be somewhat of a downer 
>>personally to be around a bunch of people with dour faces at a party.
>
>This is all you. No response from me on this....

Um.  What do you call the quoted text above this line then?  Hint: 
Try deleting parts of the email you feel no response is necessary to.

>>If I notice this situation, and don't find it enjoyable, does that 
>>automatically make me judgemental?  Hmm.
>No, this doesn't make you judgemental. We all have preferences for 
>our likes and dislikes. Its when we judge other people for thiers is 
>when we are judgemental. I don't dig country music. But there are 
>people who vibe off it much the same way I vibe on house. I don't 
>have to like their music preferences, and I certainly have no right 
>to judge them for theirs.

I don't recall anyone stating that hipsters should be put to 
death?!  They're annoying.  That's an opinion, not a judgement.

>>In another online community I belong to there is a saying "Assume 
>>goodwill."  The idea is that in the absence of strong proof to the 
>>contrary, one should always assume good will from others in the community.
>
>This doesn't mean you have to embrace people just to assume 
>goodwill.  I both club and rave. I dress the part of either. I've 
>been accused of as you say being an "ultra cool posers and 
>pseudo-hipsters". I'm don't even really know what that means. I 
>laugh because its just pure ignorance.

Well, it's good that you have a sense of humor, but doesn't it make 
more sense to alleviate your ignorance rather than just laugh at it?


>>But the idea of assume goodwill cuts both ways.  Your are right 
>>that we should assume goodwill from the utlra cool posers and 
>>pseudo-hipsters that wouldn't give many people on this list the 
>>time of day.  After all they are probably just lonely and looking 
>>for a real human connection, but totally clueless about how to find 
>>one and afraid to find out what would happen if they did.
>
>How do you come to this conclusion another human is lonely or 
>looking for real human connection just from looking at them? Who 
>gives a shit if another assumes goodwill on you? I worry about 
>whether or not I'm assuming goodwill on myself. I find this allows 
>me to direct goodwill onto others without thinking about it 
>naturally, and its usually waranted and appropriate.

You make assumptions about yourself?  It's possible to assess 
likelihood from visual observations.  Hey, the house is burning down, 
I should probably leave.  Hey, there's someone in the club acting 
funny, they probably have a motivation for doing so.


>>But by the same argument we should assume goodwill from those that 
>>criticize them.  They're just practicing discriminating awareness.
>
>Wrong, its just people being ignorant. Its perpectuating 
>discrimanation, not praticing discrimanting awareness. In my eyes 
>there is no such they as discriminating awareness. That could be a 
>whole other discussion however.

Bummer.  Discrimination is often based on plentiful facts, not a dearth.


>>I've found "assume goodwill" to be a very challenging and 
>>insightful little mantra.  Try it yourself and you might find the same.
>
>I guess the easy response to this would be to say rise above the 
>challenge. I realize life is not always that simple. But we need to 
>start somewhere. And that somewhere is within ourselves. Not within 
>the judgement of others. Next time you find yourself in that 
>situation, smile and remember why you are there at that particular 
>moment, hopefully its the music!

Sweet!  So when you wake up, and I'm robbing your house, remember, 
you're there for sleep!

up the stage at a FREE celebration of 22 years of Hip-Hop radio!!!

Every year, the hottest talent on the planet reps lovely for The =20
Greatest Show on Earth: The Drum, at KZSU Stanford. This year, the =20
world's longest-running Hip-Hop show brings the ruckus once again, =20
with a mega-lineup. . .and yes, it's FREE, and all ages. So come get =20
some!!! =46rom 1PM - 5PM at Casino Meadow in Golden Gate Park, it's =20
gonna be one to tell your great-grandkids about. . .for Real real.


=EF=BF=BC

"No sage or savior has ever endorsed greed and gluttony as a path =20
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and =20
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras, =20
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and =20
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can =20
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and =20
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond =20
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative =20
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in =20
squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of =20
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will =20
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

On 8/25/06, Apollo <apollo@speakeasy.org> wrote:
>
> Come out and *Bang The Drum* on *August 27th, *as* 22 DJs *and* 22 MCs *blow
> up the stage at a FREE celebration of 22 years of Hip-Hop radio!!!
>
> Every year, the hottest talent on the planet reps lovely for The Greatest
> Show on Earth: *The Drum, *at* KZSU Stanford*. This year, the world's
> longest-running Hip-Hop show brings the ruckus once again, with a
> mega-lineup. . .and yes, it's FREE, and all ages. So come get some!!! From
> *1PM - 5PM *at* Casino Meadow *in* Golden Gate Park,* it's gonna be one to
> tell your great-grandkids about. . .for Real real.
>
>
> Of course we'll keep it going later that night, with a bangin' afterparty
> from *10PM-2AM *at* Club Mighty: 119 Utah St. *in* San Francisco*.
>
> So make sure you tune in to *90.1FM KZSU Stanford* for up-to-the-minute
> details, and forward the info to your folks. . .or they'll be mad atcha!!!

> "No sage or savior has ever endorsed greed and gluttony as a path toward
> social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and enlightened people
> come to us from all cultures and all eras, sometimes knowing of each other
> but more often not.  Socrates and Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and
> Martin Buber -- no one can find in their lives and words a jot of support
> for a political and economic regime that encourages the acquisition of
> wealth far beyond what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the
> restorative pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and
> work in squalor."
> -Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.
>
> "Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the
> rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become
> visible."
> -Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

A lot of them are vegan, a lot of them eat giant steaks just to fuck with the vegan ones.
> 
> They are, by and large, nice, totally nonviolent (unless they're being violent in an ironic way), and mainly guilty of cliqueish behavior.  Their only "macho" issues are occasional beer/coke abuse spurred on by friends' excesses.
> 
> They are not the people hitting on anybody's wife, getting huffy on the dancefloor, or anything.  By and large, they're off having fun.  They u may act a little too cool for school now and then but they're not causing trouble.

Britannia rules the raves again 

Partying like it's 1989? These days, as rave veteran Sarah Champion discovers, the kids are as young as 12, the drug is laughing gas, the venues are forest glades and the music is harder and faster. One thing hasn't changed, though - trying to keep one step ahead of the police

Observer blog: Rafael Behr gets misty eyed and nostalgic. Share your eighties memories with him <http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/observer/archives/2006/08/26/bang_bang_squel.html#more>here


Sunday August 27, 2006
<http://www.observer.co.uk>The Observer 

Is this it? We pass a Little Chef and turn off the A road into a shadowy lay-by. It's the second to last Saturday in August, yet as dark as November with a steady drizzle. Our beams illuminate a chain of parked cars. One flashes in welcome, as if to say, 'Yes, you're here.' We take a slot near the rear of the convoy. A figure in a rain jacket moves along the line, urgently barking: 'The police have blocked the road, we've got to go now.' A 100 or so shapes emerge from steamed-up vehicles, bass blasting from each. The buzz is infectious, everyone primed for action.

This is the culmination of a day's frantic texting and posting on internet forums. I had to find out for myself whether there was any truth behind the headlines declaring a rave revival this summer. Their eyes on the drinking mayhem in our cities, the police appear to have been caught off guard in the past three months by a series of well-organised raves that arrived out of nowhere. In May Cornwall police broke up a party of 2,000 in Davidstow, seizing £3,000 in cash, drugs worth £40,000 and 12 lorries loaded with sound equipment. More raves followed. Was this another summer of love? Or a bunch of old clubbers who never went away, joined by bumper crowds due to July's heat wave? As a veteran of the 80s scene - both as a clubber and dance music journalist - I was curious.

<http://arts.guardian.co.uk/features/story/0,,1859099,00.html#article_continue>Article continues
[]


http://arts.guardian.co.uk/features/story/0,,1859099,00.html#article_continue



MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo 

Tribenet:   <http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k>http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k 
                
House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"Americans like to talk about (or be told about) Democracy but, when put to the test, usually find it to be an 'inconvenience.' We have opted instead for an authoritarian system disguised as a Democracy. We pay through the nose for an enormous joke-of-a-government, let it push us around, and then wonder how all those assholes got in there." - Frank Zappa 

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

200 riot police break up illegal rave 

· One officer suffers severed finger, eight more injured 
· Patrol car set on fire as CS gas used to disperse 1,000 

Paul Lewis
Monday August 28, 2006
<http://www.guardian.co.uk>The Guardian 

Two hundred riot police from five counties used CS gas, dogs and batons to disperse 1,000 ravers at an illegal party in Essex on Saturday night. Riots broke out in a corn field next to the village of Ickleton, near Saffron Walden, as partygoers clashed with police in scenes reminiscent of the zenith of the free party movement in the late 1980s. 

The violence, which flared up sporadically until early yesterday, was sparked when a small delegation of officers tried to negotiate the break-up of the party but met "unprecedented and ferocious" resistance, police said. A police car was set on fire and nine officers were wounded during the clashes, with injuries to police including a suspected broken collarbone and a severed finger. At least two revellers were also injured.

Subject: [sfraves] WR: My Hella Funny Flip Friday Night...

So like my 1st Cousin from Australlia, Mitchie,  was here like since last
Wed night to Sat night... Hello 2day

http://i96.photobucket.com/albums/l188/YummyBeats/Mitchie-s%20Visit%20August%202006-%20Fam%20stuff/zebulon008.jpg

... like last time i saw her was like over ummmm... i dunno.. hella years
ago... last time she spent like 2 weeks here & I had a car & we went out
everywhere :)  This time... she went out 2 Days in a row w/ my Uncle, none
of us really got to spend time w/ her.. la la la... my Mom was even sad
that she didn't get to take her Shopping...

So anywaze.. Friday... my like ok.. see.. my mom has like this misplacing
her emotion bullshit thingie goin' on & she always misdirects her shit to
other people when she's feelin' like crap... so Friday she totally took it
out on me 'cause she was hurt that she well.. what i mentioned above... so
I dunno..i kinda got outta the house early & went to the City 'cause Mr
Paulie Paul (Flash) Gordon sent out a myspace BB that he was gonna be
spinning @ this food place/ bar thingie in SOMA on Natoma called
Zebulon... "interesting" i thought.. so yeah.. it's been 4ever since we
kicked it...

I got there & like as soon as i well.. OK.. 1st off... I saw like all
these mondo yuppies hangin' out there... like outside... so i was all like
ummm... OK... but i heard these Yummy deep house beats from inside.. so i
went in & looked around.... people eating this Froo Froo Shee Shee food...
well.. i peaked @ the menu b43 i walked inside & like other people havin'
drinks... ok... then i looked up @ the Balcony/ Loft Thingie & saw Paulie
all up there mixing... LOL.. Hello 2day.. & pointed @ him & smiled & he
pointed back & waved a record @ me.. LOL.. it was Dope...

So I like manuvered my way through the crowd.... this place was packed w/
people eating & drinking & the tables were so close together... next thing
i know.. i hear someone call my name & it ended up being my cousin
Angeline who i ain't seen in a few months (another 1st cousin) & we talked
for like hella minutes about Mitchie & stuff... it was Dope & unexpected
'cause YAAAY.. REUNION!! :)  But yeah man.. it was just funny as hell
bumping into her &* like seein her lil' social group of Homies & shit :)

So I made my way up to the loft thingie where Paulie was... we talked & I
met the promoter of the happy hour House thingie... lol... He's CooL..
Ummm.. let's call him Tom for now... Tom for now.. really nice guy...
actually.. originally from Sac then moved to the City to further his
career as a house DJ...  Sweet! :)  Then i met more people, all House
Heads & 1/2 of them from Sac too :)  So that was Dope!  Actually... i
found out that Zebulon was their Remedy preparty meet up... so yeah.. i
met 1 of the crews that hit up Remedy.. Lol... it was Wicked!  They are
all Groovy people! :)

So I'm down in the 1st floor of the Resturaunt/ Bar place... talkin' to
another one of the Remedy Preparty OG from Sac Chicas... let's call her
Fancis for now... she was tellin me that Zebulon is a Filipino owned
joint.. just then... 1 of the owners, Ed, came by & gave us like 2 cups of
ooh.. ummm.. this expensive wine.. forgot the name... then Francis for now
introduced me to Ed... so we talk & talk... ok.. now check this shit
out... 'cause i knew he looked familiar & i asked him what high school he
went to.. then I told him my cousin Mylee went to that school... & he liek
ok.. the whole time we're talkin', he had this like kinda perplexed look
on his face... so when i told him Mylee's last name was Pascual.. he
tripped out..

Turns out my cousin went to a different high school & he knew 'cause he
was married to her.. Heeeeeeeeello 2Daaaaaaay... so like yeah.. this Owner
Dude, Ed, is my cousin... so we talked about all the recent family parties
& if he went & i went & la la la la.. trippy shit man... I mean.. we ain't
seen each other in like man.. amost as long as i ain't seen Mitchie... so
yeah... this was heeeeeella trippy :)  So yeah.. i kinda milked the whole
"well I'm related to the owner" card & got free drinks the whole night :P 
I mean.. he let me.. so i did!!!  LOLOLMAO  But yeah.. for now... Zebulon
is primarily like a lunch/ dinner/ drinks place.... mainly opened during
happy hour wait...

http://www.zebulonsf.com/

but yeah... Ed's workin' on getting the proper liscences & permits to make
that place run longer then 10PM on the weekends & I told him I'll help him
w/ that & stuff since I still got that SFLNC knowledge in me still & know
a few people in City Hall in the City who could help things :)  So when
this becomes a legit venue y'all... u know what's gonna go down :P  Hello
2day!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!

BUt it was a fun night... the music was Sick... Paulie's set was Yummy the
1st time.. he strait just went with this "Sexy" deep loungie house vibe...
then Tom for Now got on next & played some like alota Tribal & Proggy
House... Then Paulie got back on & played some like ok... Salsa, Basanova,
Sexy House, some really deep proggy Breaks.. I mean.. deep deep, & some
SExy House Covers of 80's songs :)

Oh yeah... in the morning.. like Mitchie woke me up @ 9AM for Breakfast
(Bless my Awesome Cousin)& by like 9PM..i was getting tired (add to that a
big ass mexican dinner that i didn't get @ Zebulon 'cause that was b4 the
Cousin connex & all the food there is no less than $7)... So i stayed 'til
like 10 then walked to bart...

OK.. here's where things get more interesting.. kinda... so i go walk up
to market & have to like cross the street... so i'm walkin' across the
cross walk & a cab seriosly like almost hits me.... like stopped @ the
point where it almost like tooked out my leg if he drove further... so I
hit the hood of his cab hard & flipped him off... then he said something
to me in like whatefer language.. then i said FUCK YOU hella loud!  right
then, when i got to the other corner.... someone yelled out "OSBY" in a
passing car... so i waved back hella laughing after that then went to
bart.

OK.. The End.. lol.. fun night :)

Oh

http://s96.photobucket.com/albums/l188/YummyBeats/ZEBULON%208-25-2006/

Take Care <3

> Britannia rules the raves again

> Partying like it's 1989? These days, as rave veteran
> Sarah Champion discovers, the kids are as young as
> 12, the drug is laughing gas, the venues are forest
> glades and the music is harder and faster. One thing
> hasn't changed, though - trying to keep one step
> ahead of the police
> 
> Observer blog: Rafael Behr gets misty eyed and
> nostalgic. Share your eighties memories with him
>
<http://blogs.guardian.co.uk/observer/archives/2006/08/26/bang_bang_squel.html#more>here
> 
> 
> Sunday August 27, 2006
> <http://www.observer.co.uk>The Observer 
> 
> Is this it? We pass a Little Chef and turn off the A
> road into a shadowy lay-by. It's the second to last
> Saturday in August, yet as dark as November with a
> steady drizzle. Our beams illuminate a chain of
> parked cars. One flashes in welcome, as if to say,
> 'Yes, you're here.' We take a slot near the rear of
> the convoy. A figure in a rain jacket moves along
> the line, urgently barking: 'The police have blocked
> the road, we've got to go now.' A 100 or so shapes
> emerge from steamed-up vehicles, bass blasting from
> each. The buzz is infectious, everyone primed for
> action.
> 
> This is the culmination of a day's frantic texting
> and posting on internet forums. I had to find out
> for myself whether there was any truth behind the
> headlines declaring a rave revival this summer.
> Their eyes on the drinking mayhem in our cities, the
> police appear to have been caught off guard in the
> past three months by a series of well-organised
> raves that arrived out of nowhere. In May Cornwall
> police broke up a party of 2,000 in Davidstow,
> seizing £3,000 in cash, drugs worth £40,000 and 12
> lorries loaded with sound equipment. More raves
> followed. Was this another summer of love? Or a
> bunch of old clubbers who never went away, joined by
> bumper crowds due to July's heat wave? As a veteran
> of the 80s scene - both as a clubber and dance music
> journalist - I was curious.
>

My friend used to live in the UK back in the early-mid 90's and he told me
about an awesome rave he went to inside a cemetery crypt. It got so hot
inside the sealed room that the walls were all wet from the sweat and steam=
.
Since it was in the crypt, you could not tell or hear anything from the
outside at all. Pure UG fun with no undesirables showing up.

> > the convoy. A figure in a rain jacket moves along

> > the road, we've got to go now.' A 100 or so shapes

> > each. The buzz is infectious, everyone primed for
> > action.

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: DIRTY w/ Chris Carter - Thurs, Sept 14 @ Mighty

DIRTY
Thursday, September 14th
Mighty (119 Utah st)
10pm-230am
21+ w/ID
$5 b4 11pm & $7 after


It's time for another rendition of Dirty, and this time Evil Breaks is
bringing back one of our favorite producers of all time to help us as
we try and raise some money for our Love Fest float. Besides the good
cause, this lineup is completely wicked, with a price and venue that
you just can't beat. This will also be one of Chris's last tours for a
while as his work visa is about to expire. 2 rooms of nasty is what
you can expect, with a great vibe and even better music.


Chris Carter (TCR/Rec. Records/Botchit & Scarper/Forged) - London, UK

Chris has established himself as a popular DJ and has toured all over
Europe as well as the USA, Asia and Australia. His mixes have been
aired on radio stations such as Radio1, Kiss, Ministry, Groovetech and
stations across Europe and the US.

Since starting to release his own productions in 1997, he has had a
steady stream of releases on a number UK based breaks labels including
TCR, Botchit + Scarper, Forged, En:Vision, Secret Agent, Track,and his
own Record Records amongst others, earning him a reputation as a
master of well-crafted left-of-centre dancefloor tunes.

His remix work includes tracks for Forged, Botchit, Cup of Chi,
En:Vision, Passenger,and most recently as Roxiller on Sober,
Functional and Broke Records.


the Evil Breakers for the night:

Aaron Jae (Evil Breaks/XM Radio/AaronJae.com)
Bam (Evil Breaks/Invibe.com)
M.O.D. (Evil Breaks)


Super Duper guest dj's:

Syd Gris (Opel Productions/Opulent Temple)
Jeffrey Allen (LOST/Bambuddha Lounge/Proton Radio)
Jared (Deep End/In Deep)
Evinrude (Renegade Ferrets/Crooked)


Sign up for our mailing list to get your chance at free tickets to
this and all of our events.....
www.EvilBreaks.com
--

On Fri, 25 Aug 2006 tsheets@saturn5.com wrote:
-&e->I thought the 80's hair-band look is coming back BIG.
-&e->
-&e->Ironically drinking cheap beer may never go out of style (unfortuanatly...)
-&e->
-&e->Streight guys wearing woman's jeans is probalby well over.
-&e->
-&e->But yeah, isn't San Francisco weird?  How you can identify someone at a club
-&e->from either being from the North side (Marina/pac heights) or the South
-&e->Side (mission/haight) in about a second?

-&e->-troy

a) 80s hair bands sucked when it was the 80s.  more so now.  you have no 
idea how much it pained me to have a guy who always dressed better than 
me, a brilliant producer, etc, show up one night with a mullet.  that 
said, I need a haircut at some point... bad hair + pink guitar... I'm 
cruisin for a bruisin.  i should write a song called 'the real 
america is in rockies' and make some money off Coors.  maybe they'll pay 
off my K car.  just kidding, no way could a K car still be running 
nowdays.

b) cheap beer has a price that is greater than any savings.  I can get 
looped on Stella Artois and I wake up dehydrated.  if I do the same with 
Miller, I feel like I was poorly treated and at the mercy of a vengeful 
god who shoots hangoverbolts from his sour malty fingers.

c) it's ok for a guy to wear women's jeans.  if it was an honest mistake.  
like, woke up after some freaky deaky, and just grabbed the wrong pants 
and somehow managed to get into them.  It's like a badge of honor.

d) i don't care where someone lives, but damn I meet some annoying people 
when I go out sometimes.  that said I've actually met some cool people 
lately.

e) Troy, I love ya man, but get your processes in check.  hint... go to 
our beloved home server and run 'top'.  you're so #1, #2, and #3 right 
now.  time to kill -clickclick9mmfullclip that crazy renegade process 
bidnis *pew*pew*pew*.

&eUU

p.s.	george, I would vote for pedro, he was cool.

Rave reviews of bygone youth

SUSAN MANSFIELD 



MATT STOKES: PILLS TO PURGE MELANCHOLY ****

COLLECTIVE GALLERY, EDINBURGH 


THE papers are proclaiming the return of the rave. Young people are once again holding illicit outdoor dance parties, keeping one step ahead of the law. This brings an extra layer of resonance to the work of Beck's Futures winner Matt Stokes, whose vast ongoing project Real Arcadia remembers the first rave era, in particular a series of cave raves which took place in the Lake District on the cusp of the 1990s. 

Real Arcadia audibly spills out of the main room at Edinburgh's Collective Gallery in this, Stokes' first solo show. There are museum-like glass cases full of ephemera - flyers, membership cards, cassette tapes, newspaper cuttings. There are snapshots from the time enlarged and framed, and a set of speakers (part of an exact replica of the cave sound system) pounding out beats by DJ Grogg. 

There is a powerful sense of youthful idealism in the handwritten flyers, the designs on the cassette sleeves individually coloured-in by the DJs, the promise of "robot lightning" and "terror strobes". All this dedication contrasts with the self-righteousness of the locals quoted in the newspapers, claiming that the "safety of the party-goers" was their first priority when they were probably more worried about getting their flowerbeds trampled on. It's a classic generation gap of youthful rebels versus middle-aged establishment, and in that sense it is timeless. 

In another sense it's sharply rooted in time, a time which seems distant, despite being only a few years ago. There's a snapshot of a raver wearing a home-designed "Rave in the Cave" T-shirt just like the one in the display case next to it, faded and stained with age. He can't have been more than 19. Where is he now? A respectable thirtysomething with kids and a job? Or one of the rave generation who succumbed to drug abuse and never resurfaced? 

http://living.scotsman.com/index.cfm?id=1270842006


There are no other possible outcomes but middle-class life or total dissolution?  :-)




MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo 

Tribenet:   <http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k>http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k 
                
House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"Americans like to talk about (or be told about) Democracy but, when put to the test, usually find it to be an 'inconvenience.' We have opted instead for an authoritarian system disguised as a Democracy. We pay through the nose for an enormous joke-of-a-government, let it push us around, and then wonder how all those assholes got in there." - Frank Zappa 

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"  
--=====================_29151000==.ALT--
